# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: satellite-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Controlling vehicle attitude requires actuators to apply the torques needed to orient the vehicle to a desired attitude, and algorithms to command the actuators based on the current attitude and specification of a desired attitude.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Before and during attitude control can be performed, **spacecraft attitude determination** must be performed, which requires sensors for absolute or relative measurement.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The broader integrated field that studies the combination of sensors, actuators and algorithms is called *guidance, navigation and control*, which also involves non-attitude concepts, such as position determination and navigation.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Spacecraft generally have an attitude determination and control system (ADCS), which includes both sensors and actuators.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] However, budget satellites (such as some cubesats), may elect for simpler attitude control systems (ACS) which use passive techniques, including the yo-yo de-spin technique and permanent magnets to control the attitude of the satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A spacecraft's attitude must typically be stabilized and controlled for a variety of reasons.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Many spacecraft have components that require articulation or pointing.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Voyager and *Galileo*, for example, were designed with scan platforms for pointing optical instruments at their targets largely independently of spacecraft orientation.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Many spacecraft, such as Mars orbiters, have solar panels that must track the Sun so they can provide electrical power to the spacecraft.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] *Cassini*'s main engine nozzles were steerable.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Knowing where to point a solar panel, or scan platform, or a nozzle — that is, how to articulate it — requires knowledge of the spacecraft's attitude.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Because a single subsystem keeps track of the spacecraft's attitude, the Sun's location, and Earth's location, it can compute the proper direction to point the appendages.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] It logically falls to the same subsystem – the Attitude and Articulation Control Subsystem (AACS), then, to manage both attitude and articulation.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The name AACS may even be carried over to a spacecraft even if it has no appendages to articulate.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Attitude is part of the description of how an object is placed in the space it occupies.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Attitude and position fully describe how an object is placed in space.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] For some applications (e.g., robotics, computer vision), it is customary to combine position and attitude together into a single description known as Pose.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Attitude can be described using a variety of methods; however, the most common are Rotation matrices, Quaternions, and Euler angles.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] While Euler angles are oftentimes the most straightforward representation to visualize, they can cause problems for highly-maneuverable systems because of a phenomenon known as Gimbal lock.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A rotation matrix, on the other hand, provides a full description of the attitude at the expense of requiring nine values instead of three.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The use of a rotation matrix can lead to increased computational expense and they can be more difficult to work with.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Quaternions offer a decent compromise in that they do not suffer from gimbal lock and only require four values to fully describe the attitude.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Attitude control of spacecraft is maintained using one of two principal approaches: spin stabilization and three-axis stabilization.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Spin stabilization is accomplished by setting the spacecraft spinning, using the gyroscopic action of the rotating spacecraft mass as the stabilizing mechanism.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Propulsion system thrusters are fired only occasionally to make desired changes in spin rate, or in the spin-stabilized attitude.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] If desired, the spinning may be stopped through the use of thrusters or by yo-yo de-spin.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The *Pioneer 10* and *Pioneer 11* probes in the outer Solar System are examples of spin-stabilized spacecraft.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Three-axis stabilization is an alternative method of spacecraft attitude control in which the spacecraft is held fixed in the desired orientation without any rotation.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] There are advantages and disadvantages to both spin stabilization and three-axis stabilization.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Three-axis controlled craft can point optical instruments and antennas without having to de-spin them, but they may have to carry out special rotating maneuvers to best utilize their fields and particle instruments.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] If thrusters are used for routine stabilization, optical observations such as imaging must be designed knowing that the spacecraft is always slowly rocking back and forth, and not always exactly predictably.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Vernier thrusters are the most common actuators, as they may be used for station keeping as well.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Thrusters must be organized as a system to provide stabilization about all three axes, and at least two thrusters are generally used in each axis to provide torque as a couple in order to prevent imparting a translation to the vehicle.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Their limitations are fuel usage, engine wear, and cycles of the control valves.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The fuel efficiency of an attitude control system is determined by its specific impulse (proportional to exhaust velocity) and the smallest torque impulse it can provide (which determines how often the thrusters must fire to provide precise control).
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Thrusters must be fired in one direction to start rotation, and again in the opposing direction if a new orientation is to be held.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Thruster systems have been used on most crewed space vehicles, including Vostok, Mercury, Gemini, Apollo, Soyuz, and the Space Shuttle.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] To minimize the fuel limitation on mission duration, auxiliary attitude control systems may be used to reduce vehicle rotation to lower levels, such as small ion thrusters that accelerate ionized gases electrically to extreme velocities, using power from solar cells.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Momentum wheels are electric motor driven rotors made to spin in the direction opposite to that required to re-orient the vehicle.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Because momentum wheels make up a small fraction of the spacecraft's mass and are computer controlled, they give precise control.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Momentum wheels are generally suspended on magnetic bearings to avoid bearing friction and breakdown problems.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Spacecraft Reaction wheels often use mechanical ball bearings.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] To maintain orientation in three dimensional space a minimum of three reaction wheels must be used, with additional units providing single failure protection.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] These are rotors spun at constant speed, mounted on gimbals to provide attitude control.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Although a CMG provides control about the two axes orthogonal to the gyro spin axis, triaxial control still requires two units.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A CMG is a bit more expensive in terms of cost and mass, because gimbals and their drive motors must be provided.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The maximum torque (but not the maximum angular momentum change) exerted by a CMG is greater than for a momentum wheel, making it better suited to large spacecraft.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A major drawback is the additional complexity, which increases the number of failure points.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] For this reason, the International Space Station uses a set of four CMGs to provide dual failure tolerance.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Small solar sails (devices that produce thrust as a reaction force induced by reflecting incident light) may be used to make small attitude control and velocity adjustments.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This application can save large amounts of fuel on a long-duration mission by producing control moments without fuel expenditure.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] For example, *Mariner 10* adjusted its attitude using its solar cells and antennas as small solar sails.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] In orbit, a spacecraft with one axis much longer than the other two will spontaneously orient so that its long axis points at the planet's center of mass.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This system has the virtue of needing no active control system or expenditure of fuel.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The upper end of the vehicle feels less gravitational pull than the lower end.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This provides a restoring torque whenever the long axis is not co-linear with the direction of gravity.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Unless some means of damping is provided, the spacecraft will oscillate about the local vertical.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Sometimes tethers are used to connect two parts of a satellite, to increase the stabilizing torque.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A problem with such tethers is that meteoroids as small as a grain of sand can part them.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Coils or (on very small satellites) permanent magnets exert a moment against the local magnetic field.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This method works only where there is a magnetic field against which to react.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] One classic field "coil" is actually in the form of a conductive tether in a planetary magnetic field.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Such a conductive tether can also generate electrical power, at the expense of orbital decay.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Conversely, by inducing a counter-current, using solar cell power, the orbit may be raised.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Due to massive variability in Earth's magnetic field from an ideal radial field, control laws based on torques coupling to this field will be highly non-linear.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Moreover, only two-axis control is available at any given time meaning that a vehicle reorient may be necessary to null all rates.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Three main types of passive attitude control exist for satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The first one uses gravity gradient, and it leads to four stable states with the long axis (axis with smallest moment of inertia) pointing towards Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] As this system has four stable states, if the satellite has a preferred orientation, e.g. a camera pointed at the planet, some way to flip the satellite and its tether end-for-end is needed.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The second passive system orients the satellite along Earth's magnetic field thanks to a magnet.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] These purely passive attitude control systems have limited pointing accuracy, because the spacecraft will oscillate around energy minima.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This drawback is overcome by adding damper, which can be hysteretic materials or a viscous damper.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The viscous damper is a small can or tank of fluid mounted in the spacecraft, possibly with internal baffles to increase internal friction.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Friction within the damper will gradually convert oscillation energy into heat dissipated within the viscous damper.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A third form of passive attitude control is aerodynamic stabilization.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This is achieved using a drag gradient, as demonstrated on the Get Away Special Passive Attitude Control Satellite (GASPACS) technology demonstration.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] In low Earth orbit, the force due to drag is many orders of magnitude more dominant than the force imparted due to gravity gradients.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] When a satellite is utilizing aerodynamic passive attitude control, air molecules from the Earth's upper atmosphere strike the satellite in such a way that the center of pressure remains behind the center of mass, similar to how the feathers on an arrow stabilize the arrow.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] GASPACS utilized a 1 m inflatable 'AeroBoom', which extended behind the satellite, creating a stabilizing torque along the satellite's velocity vector.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Another form of passive attitude control is yo-yo de-spin.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Yo-yo de-spin devices are controversial as they generate space debris, and are primarily used for deep-space spacecraft.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Control algorithms are computer programs that receive data from vehicle sensors and derive the appropriate commands to the actuators to rotate the vehicle to the desired attitude.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The algorithms range from very simple, e.g. proportional control, to complex nonlinear estimators or many in-between types, depending on mission requirements.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Typically, the attitude control algorithms are part of the software running on the computer hardware, which receives commands from the ground and formats vehicle data telemetry for transmission to a ground station.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The attitude control algorithms are written and implemented based on requirement for a particular attitude maneuver.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Asides the implementation of passive attitude control such as the gravity-gradient stabilization, most spacecraft make use of active control which exhibits a typical attitude control loop.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The design of the control algorithm depends on the actuator to be used for the specific attitude maneuver although using a simple *proportional–integral–derivative controller* (*PID controller*) satisfies most control needs.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The appropriate commands to the actuators are obtained based on error signals described as the difference between the measured and desired attitude.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The error signals are commonly measured as euler angles (Φ, θ, Ψ), however an alternative to this could be described in terms of direction cosine matrix or error quaternions.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] where $T_{c}$ is the control torque, e is the attitude deviation signal, and $K_{\text{p}},K_{\text{i}},K_{\text{d}}$ are the PID controller parameters.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A simple implementation of this can be the application of the proportional control for nadir pointing making use of either momentum or reaction wheels as actuators.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This control algorithm also affects momentum dumping.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Another important and common control algorithm involves the concept of detumbling, which is attenuating the angular momentum of the spacecraft.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The need to detumble the spacecraft arises from the uncontrollable state after release from the launch vehicle.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Most spacecraft in low Earth orbit (LEO) makes use of magnetic detumbling concept which utilizes the effect of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The control algorithm is called the B-Dot controller and relies on magnetic coils or torque rods as control actuators.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The control law is based on the measurement of the rate of change of body-fixed magnetometer signals.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] where m is the commanded magnetic dipole moment of the magnetic torquer and K is the proportional gain and ${\dot {B}}$ is the rate of change of the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A spacecraft's ADCS system generally begins detumbling at the start of the mission, either autonomously or when commanded.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Nadir pointing mode and sun pointing mode, among others, are implemented by using actuators to put the spacecraft into a Y-Thomson spin, named after William T.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Thomson, whereby the spacecraft completes one full rotation about its orbit normal axis as it completes one full revolution about the primary body.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] In a geocentric satellite, a Y-Thomson spin is often used to point one face of the spacecraft to face the center of gravity of the Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This spin aligns the spacecraft body frame with the orbit's tangent-normal-radial reference frame.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] When combined with a nadir-pointing deployable boom, gravity-gradient forces passively stabilize the spacecraft's attitude.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Many sensors generate outputs that reflect the rate of change in attitude.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] These require a known initial attitude, or external information to use them to determine attitude.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Many of this class of sensor have some noise, leading to inaccuracies if not corrected by absolute attitude sensors.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Gyroscopes are devices that sense rotation in three-dimensional space without reliance on the observation of external objects.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Classically, a gyroscope consists of a spinning mass, but there are also "ring laser gyros" utilizing coherent light reflected around a closed path.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Another type of "gyro" is a hemispherical resonator gyro where a crystal cup shaped like a wine glass can be driven into oscillation just as a wine glass "sings" as a finger is rubbed around its rim.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] The orientation of the oscillation is fixed in inertial space, so measuring the orientation of the oscillation relative to the spacecraft can be used to sense the motion of the spacecraft with respect to inertial space.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Motion reference units are a kind of inertial measurement unit with single- or multi-axis motion sensors.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Some multi-axis MRUs are capable of measuring roll, pitch, yaw and heave.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This class of sensors sense the position or orientation of fields, objects or other phenomena outside the spacecraft.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A *horizon sensor* is an optical instrument that detects light from the 'limb' of Earth's atmosphere, i.e., at the horizon.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Thermal infrared sensing is often used, which senses the comparative warmth of the atmosphere, compared to the much colder cosmic background.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This sensor provides orientation with respect to Earth about two orthogonal axes.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] It tends to be less precise than sensors based on stellar observation.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Sometimes referred to as an Earth sensor.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Thus, the horizon sensor provides pitch and roll measurements, and the gyro provides yaw.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A *Sun sensor* is a device that senses the direction to the Sun.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This can be as simple as some solar cells and shades, or as complex as a steerable telescope, depending on mission requirements.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] An *Earth sensor* is a device that senses the direction to Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] It is usually an infrared camera; nowadays the main method to detect attitude is the star tracker, but Earth sensors are still integrated in satellites for their low cost and reliability.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A *star tracker* is an optical device that measures the position(s) of star(s) using photocell(s) or a camera.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] It uses magnitude of brightness and spectral type to identify and then calculate the relative position of stars around it.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] A *magnetometer* is a device that senses magnetic field strength and, when used in a three-axis triad, magnetic field direction.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] As a spacecraft navigational aid, sensed field strength and direction is compared to a map of Earth's magnetic field stored in the memory of an on-board or ground-based guidance computer.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] If spacecraft position is known then attitude can be inferred.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Attitude cannot be measured directly by any single measurement, and so must be calculated (or estimated) from a set of measurements (often using different sensors).
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Static attitude estimation methods are solutions to Wahba's problem.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Many solutions have been proposed, notably Davenport's q-method, QUEST, TRIAD, and singular value decomposition.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Kalman filtering can be used to sequentially estimate the attitude, as well as the angular rate.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Because attitude dynamics (combination of rigid body dynamics and attitude kinematics) are non-linear, a linear Kalman filter is not sufficient.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Because attitude dynamics is not very non-linear, the Extended Kalman filter is usually sufficient (however Crassidis and Markely demonstrated that the Unscented Kalman filter could be used, and can provide benefits in cases where the initial estimate is poor).
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] Multiple methods have been proposed, however the Multiplicative Extended Kalman Filter (MEKF) is by far the most common approach.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This approach utilizes the multiplicative formulation of the error quaternion, which allows for the unity constraint on the quaternion to be better handled.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] It is also common to use a technique known as dynamic model replacement, where the angular rate is not estimated directly, but rather the measured angular rate from the gyro is used directly to propagate the rotational dynamics forward in time.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This is valid for most applications as gyros are typically far more precise than one's knowledge of disturbance torques acting on the system (which is required for precise estimation of the angular rate).
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] For some sensors and applications (such as spacecraft using magnetometers) the precise location must also be known.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] While pose estimation can be employed, for spacecraft it is usually sufficient to estimate the position (via Orbit determination) separate from the attitude estimation.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] For terrestrial vehicles and spacecraft operating near the Earth, the advent of Satellite navigation systems allows for precise position knowledge to be obtained easily.
[src:satellite-systems/attitude-control] This problem becomes more complicated for deep space vehicles, or terrestrial vehicles operating in Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) denied environments (see Navigation).
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] A **communications satellite** is an artificial satellite that relays and amplifies radio telecommunication signals via a transponder; it creates a communication channel between a source transmitter and a receiver at different locations on Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Communications satellites are used for television, telephone, radio, internet, and military applications.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] However, most form satellite constellations in low Earth orbit, where ground antennas must track the satellites and switch between them frequently.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The radio waves used for telecommunications links travel by line of sight and so are obstructed by the curve of the Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The purpose of communications satellites is to relay the signal around the curve of the Earth allowing communication between widely separated geographical points.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Communications satellites operate across a wide range of radio and microwave frequencies.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] To avoid signal interference, international organizations have regulations for which frequency ranges or "bands" certain organizations are allowed to use.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] This allocation of bands minimizes the risk of signal interference.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Clarke published an article titled "Extraterrestrial Relays" in the British magazine *Wireless World*.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The article described the fundamentals behind the deployment of artificial satellites in geostationary orbits to relay radio signals.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Clarke is often quoted as being the inventor of the concept of the communications satellite, and the term 'Clarke Belt' is employed as a description of the orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The first artificial Earth satellite was Sputnik 1, which was put into orbit by the Soviet Union on 4 October 1957.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] It was developed by Mikhail Tikhonravov and Sergey Korolev, building on work by Konstantin Tsiolkovsky.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Sputnik 1 was equipped with an on-board radio transmitter that worked on two frequencies of 20.005 and 40.002 MHz, or 7 and 15 meters wavelength.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The satellite was not placed in orbit to send data from one point on Earth to another, but the radio transmitter was meant to study the properties of radio wave distribution throughout the ionosphere.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The launch of Sputnik 1 was a major step in the exploration of space and rocket development, and marks the beginning of the Space Age.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] There are two major classes of communications satellites, *passive* and *active*.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Passive satellites only reflect the signal coming from the source, toward the direction of the receiver.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] With passive satellites, the reflected signal is not amplified at the satellite, and only a small amount of the transmitted energy actually reaches the receiver.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Since the satellite is so far above Earth, the radio signal is attenuated due to free-space path loss, so the signal received on Earth is very weak.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Active satellites, on the other hand, amplify the received signal before retransmitting it to the receiver on the ground.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Passive satellites were the first communications satellites, but are little used now.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Work that was begun in the field of electrical intelligence gathering at the United States Naval Research Laboratory in 1951 led to a project named Communication Moon Relay.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] After achieving the first transoceanic communication between Washington, D.C., and Hawaii on 23 January 1956, this system was publicly inaugurated and put into formal production in January 1960.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The first satellite purpose-built to actively relay communications was Project SCORE, led by Advanced Research Projects Agency (ARPA) and launched on 18 December 1958, which used a tape recorder to carry a stored voice message, as well as to receive, store, and retransmit messages.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] It was used to send a Christmas greeting to the world from U.S.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The satellite also executed several realtime transmissions before the non-rechargeable batteries failed on 30 December 1958 after eight hours of actual operation.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The direct successor to SCORE was another ARPA-led project called Courier.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Courier 1B was launched on 4 October 1960 to explore whether it would be possible to establish a global military communications network by using "delayed repeater" satellites, which receive and store information until commanded to rebroadcast them.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] After 17 days, a command system failure ended communications from the satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] NASA's satellite applications program launched the first artificial satellite used for passive relay communications in Echo 1 on 12 August 1960.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Echo 1 was an aluminized balloon satellite acting as a passive reflector of microwave signals.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Communication signals were bounced off the satellite from one point on Earth to another.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] This experiment sought to establish the feasibility of worldwide broadcasts of telephone, radio, and television signals.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Telstar was the first active, direct relay communications commercial satellite and marked the first transatlantic transmission of television signals.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Another passive relay experiment primarily intended for military communications purposes was Project West Ford, which was led by Massachusetts Institute of Technology's Lincoln Laboratory.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] After an initial failure in 1961, a launch on 9 May 1963 dispersed 350 million copper needle dipoles to create a passive reflecting belt.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Even though only about half of the dipoles properly separated from each other, the project was able to successfully experiment and communicate using frequencies in the SHF X band spectrum.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] An immediate antecedent of the geostationary satellites was the Hughes Aircraft Company's Syncom 2, launched on 26 July 1963.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Syncom 2 was the first communications satellite in a geosynchronous orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] It revolved around the Earth once per day at constant speed, but because it still had north–south motion, special equipment was needed to track it.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Its successor, Syncom 3, launched on 19 July 1964, was the first geostationary communications satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Syncom 3 obtained a geosynchronous orbit, without a north–south motion, making it appear from the ground as a stationary object in the sky.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] A direct extension of the passive experiments of Project West Ford was the Lincoln Experimental Satellite program, also conducted by the Lincoln Laboratory on behalf of the United States Department of Defense.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The LES-1 active communications satellite was launched on 11 February 1965 to explore the feasibility of active solid-state X band long-range military communications.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] A total of nine satellites were launched between 1965 and 1976 as part of this series.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] In the United States, 1962 saw the creation of the Communications Satellite Corporation (COMSAT) private corporation, which was subject to instruction by the US Government on matters of national policy.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Over the next two years, international negotiations led to the Intelsat Agreements, which in turn led to the launch of Intelsat 1, also known as Early Bird, on 6 April 1965, and which was the first commercial communications satellite to be placed in geosynchronous orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Subsequent Intelsat launches in the 1960s provided multi-destination service and video, audio, and data service to ships at sea (Intelsat 2 in 1966–67), and the completion of a fully global network with Intelsat 3 in 1969–70.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] When Intelsat was launched, the United States was the only launch source outside of the Soviet Union, who did not participate in the Intelsat agreements.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The Soviet Union launched its first communications satellite on 23 April 1965 as part of the Molniya program.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] This program was also unique at the time for its use of what then became known as the Molniya orbit, which describes a highly elliptical orbit, with two high apogees daily over the northern hemisphere.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] This orbit provides a long dwell time over Russian territory as well as over Canada at higher latitudes than geostationary orbits over the equator.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] In the 2020s, the popularity of low Earth orbit satellite internet constellations providing relatively low-cost internet services led to reducing demand for new geostationary orbit communications satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Communications satellites usually have one of three primary types of orbit, while other orbital classifications are used to further specify orbital details.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] MEO and LEO are non-geostationary orbit (NGSO).
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] As satellites in MEO and LEO orbit the Earth faster, they do not remain visible in the sky to a fixed point on Earth continually like a geostationary satellite, but appear to a ground observer to cross the sky and "set" when they go behind the Earth beyond the visible horizon.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Therefore, to provide continuous communications capability with these lower orbits requires a larger number of satellites, so that one of these satellites will always be visible in the sky for transmission of communication signals.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] However, due to their closer distance to the Earth, LEO or MEO satellites can communicate to ground with reduced latency and at lower power than would be required from a geosynchronous orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] A low Earth orbit (LEO) typically is a circular orbit about 160 to 2,000 kilometres (99 to 1,243 mi) above the Earth's surface and, correspondingly, a period (time to revolve around the Earth) of about 90 minutes.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Because of their low altitude, these satellites are only visible from within a radius of roughly 1,000 kilometres (620 mi) from the sub-satellite point.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] In addition, satellites in low Earth orbit change their position relative to the ground position quickly.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] So even for local applications, many satellites are needed if the mission requires uninterrupted connectivity.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Low-Earth-orbiting satellites are less expensive to launch into orbit than geostationary satellites and, due to proximity to the ground, do not require as high signal strength (signal strength falls off as the square of the distance from the source, so the effect is considerable).
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Thus there is a trade off between the number of satellites and their cost.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] In addition, there are important differences in the onboard and ground equipment needed to support the two types of missions.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] A group of satellites working in concert is known as a satellite constellation.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Two such constellations, intended to provide satellite phone and low-speed data services, primarily to remote areas, are the Iridium and Globalstar systems.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The Iridium system has 66 satellites, which orbital inclination of 86.4° and inter-satellite links provide service availability over the entire surface of Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Starlink is a satellite internet constellation operated by SpaceX, that aims for global satellite Internet access coverage.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] It is also possible to offer discontinuous coverage using a low-Earth-orbit satellite capable of storing data received while passing over one part of Earth and transmitting it later while passing over another part.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] This will be the case with the CASCADE system of Canada's CASSIOPE communications satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Another system using this store and forward method is Orbcomm.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] A medium Earth orbit is a satellite in orbit somewhere between 2,000 and 35,786 kilometres (1,243 and 22,236 mi) above the Earth's surface.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] MEO satellites are similar to LEO satellites in functionality.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] MEO satellites are visible for much longer periods of time than LEO satellites, usually between 2 and 8 hours.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] MEO satellites have a larger coverage area than LEO satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] A MEO satellite's longer duration of visibility and wider footprint means fewer satellites are needed in a MEO network than a LEO network.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] One disadvantage is that a MEO satellite's distance gives it a longer time delay and weaker signal than a LEO satellite, although these limitations are not as severe as those of a GEO satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Like LEOs, these satellites do not maintain a stationary distance from the Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] This is in contrast to the geostationary orbit, where satellites are always 35,786 kilometres (22,236 mi) from Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Typically the orbit of a medium Earth orbit satellite is about 16,000 kilometres (10,000 mi) above Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] In various patterns, these satellites make the trip around Earth in anywhere from 2 to 8 hours.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] To an observer on Earth, a satellite in a geostationary orbit appears motionless, in a fixed position in the sky.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] This is because it revolves around the Earth at Earth's own angular velocity (one revolution per sidereal day, in an equatorial orbit).
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] A geostationary orbit is useful for communications because ground antennas can be aimed at the satellite without their having to track the satellite's motion.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] In applications that require many ground antennas, such as DirecTV distribution, the savings in ground equipment can more than outweigh the cost and complexity of placing a satellite into orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] By 2000, Hughes Space and Communications (now Boeing Satellite Development Center) had built nearly 40 percent of the more than one hundred satellites in service worldwide.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Geostationary satellites must operate above the equator and therefore appear lower on the horizon as the receiver gets farther from the equator.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] This will cause problems for extreme northerly latitudes, affecting connectivity and causing multipath interference (caused by signals reflecting off the ground and into the ground antenna).
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Thus, for areas close to the North (and South) Pole, a geostationary satellite may appear below the horizon.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Therefore, Molniya orbit satellites have been launched, mainly in Russia, to alleviate this problem.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Molniya orbits can be an appealing alternative in such cases.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The Molniya orbit is highly inclined, guaranteeing good elevation over selected positions during the northern portion of the orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] (Elevation is the extent of the satellite's position above the horizon.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The Molniya orbit is designed so that the satellite spends the great majority of its time over the far northern latitudes, during which its ground footprint moves only slightly.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Its period is one half day, so that the satellite is available for operation over the targeted region for six to nine hours every second revolution.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] In this way a constellation of three Molniya satellites (plus in-orbit spares) can provide uninterrupted coverage.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The first satellite of the Molniya series was launched on 23 April 1965 and was used for experimental transmission of TV signals from a Moscow uplink station to downlink stations located in Siberia and the Russian Far East, in Norilsk, Khabarovsk, Magadan and Vladivostok.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] In November 1967 Soviet engineers created a unique system of national TV network of satellite television, called Orbita, that was based on Molniya satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] In the United States, the National Polar-orbiting Operational Environmental Satellite System (NPOESS) was established in 1994 to consolidate the polar satellite operations of NASA (National Aeronautics and Space Administration) NOAA (National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration).
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] NPOESS manages a number of satellites for various purposes; for example, METSAT for meteorological satellite, EUMETSAT for the European branch of the program, and METOP for meteorological operations.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] These orbits are Sun synchronous, meaning that they cross the equator at the same local time each day.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] For example, the satellites in the NPOESS (civilian) orbit will cross the equator, going from south to north, at times 1:30 P.M., 5:30 P.M., and 9:30 P.M.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] There are plans and initiatives to bring dedicated communications satellite beyond geostationary orbits.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] NASA proposed LunaNet as a data network aiming to provide a "Lunar Internet" for cis-lunar spacecraft and Installations.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The Moonlight Initiative is an equivalent ESA project that is stated to be compatible and providing navigational services for the lunar surface.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Both programmes are satellite constellations of several satellites in various orbits around the Moon.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Other orbits are also planned to be used.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Positions in the Earth-Moon-Libration points are also proposed for communication satellites covering the Moon alike communication satellites in geosynchronous orbit cover the Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Also, dedicated communication satellites in orbits around Mars supporting different missions on surface and other orbits are considered, such as the Mars Telecommunications Orbiter.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The bandwidth available from a satellite depends upon the number of transponders provided by the satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Each service (TV, Voice, Internet, radio) requires a different amount of bandwidth for transmission.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] This is typically known as link budgeting and a network simulator can be used to arrive at the exact value.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Allocating frequencies to satellite services is a complicated process which requires international coordination and planning.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] This is carried out under the auspices of the International Telecommunication Union (ITU).
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Within these regions, frequency bands are allocated to various satellite services, although a given service may be allocated different frequency bands in different regions.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The first and historically most important application for communication satellites was in intercontinental long distance telephony.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The fixed Public Switched Telephone Network relays telephone calls from land line telephones to an Earth station, where they are then transmitted to a geostationary satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Improvements in submarine communications cables through the use of fiber-optics caused some decline in the use of satellites for fixed telephony in the late 20th century.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Satellite communications are still used in many applications today.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Remote islands such as Ascension Island, Saint Helena, Diego Garcia, and Easter Island, where no submarine cables are in service, need satellite telephones.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] There are also regions of some continents and countries where landline telecommunications are rare to non existent, for example large regions of South America, Africa, Canada, China, Russia, and Australia.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Satellite communications also provide connection to the edges of Antarctica and Greenland.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Other land use for satellite phones are rigs at sea, a backup for hospitals, military, and recreation.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Ships at sea, as well as planes, often use satellite phones.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Satellite phone systems can be accomplished by a number of means.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] On a large scale, often there will be a local telephone system in an isolated area with a link to the telephone system in a main land area.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] There are also services that will patch a radio signal to a telephone system.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] In this example, almost any type of satellite can be used.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Satellite phones connect directly to a constellation of either geostationary or low-Earth-orbit satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Calls are then forwarded to a satellite teleport connected to the Public Switched Telephone Network .
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] As television became the main market, its demand for simultaneous delivery of relatively few signals of large bandwidth to many receivers being a more precise match for the capabilities of geosynchronous comsats.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Two satellite types are used for North American television and radio: Direct broadcast satellite (DBS), and Fixed Service Satellite (FSS).
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The definitions of FSS and DBS satellites outside of North America, especially in Europe, are a bit more ambiguous.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Most satellites used for direct-to-home television in Europe have the same high power output as DBS-class satellites in North America, but use the same linear polarization as FSS-class satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Examples of these are the Astra, Eutelsat, and Hotbird spacecraft in orbit over the European continent.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Because of this, the terms FSS and DBS are more so used throughout the North American continent, and are uncommon in Europe.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Fixed Service Satellites use the C band, and the lower portions of the Ku band.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] FSS satellites are also used to distribute national cable channels to cable television headends.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Free-to-air satellite TV channels are also usually distributed on FSS satellites in the Ku band.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The Intelsat Americas 5, Galaxy 10R and AMC 3 satellites over North America provide a quite large amount of FTA channels on their Ku band transponders.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] A direct broadcast satellite is a communications satellite that transmits to small DBS satellite dishes (usually 18 to 24 inches or 45 to 60 cm in diameter).
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Direct broadcast satellites generally operate in the upper portion of the microwave Ku band.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] DBS technology is used for DTH-oriented (Direct-To-Home) satellite TV services, such as DirecTV, DISH Network and Orby TV in the United States, Bell Satellite TV and Shaw Direct in Canada, Freesat and Sky in the UK, Ireland, and New Zealand and DSTV in South Africa.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Operating at lower frequency and lower power than DBS, FSS satellites require a much larger dish for reception (3 to 8 feet (1 to 2.5 m) in diameter for Ku band, and 12 feet (3.6 m) or larger for C band).
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] They use linear polarization for each of the transponders' RF input and output (as opposed to circular polarization used by DBS satellites), but this is a minor technical difference that users do not notice.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] FSS satellite technology was also originally used for DTH satellite TV from the late 1970s to the early 1990s in the United States in the form of TVRO (Television Receive Only) receivers and dishes.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] It was also used in its Ku band form for the now-defunct Primestar satellite TV service.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Some satellites have been launched that have transponders in the Ka band, such as DirecTV's SPACEWAY-1 satellite, and Anik F2.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] NASA and ISRO have also launched experimental satellites carrying Ka band beacons recently.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Some manufacturers have also introduced special antennas for mobile reception of DBS television.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Using Global Positioning System (GPS) technology as a reference, these antennas automatically re-aim to the satellite no matter where or how the vehicle (on which the antenna is mounted) is situated.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] These mobile satellite antennas are popular with some recreational vehicle owners.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Such mobile DBS antennas are also used by JetBlue Airways for DirecTV (supplied by LiveTV, a subsidiary of JetBlue), which passengers can view on-board on LCD screens mounted in the seats.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Satellite radio offers audio broadcast services in some countries, notably the United States.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Mobile services allow listeners to roam a continent, listening to the same audio programming anywhere.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] A satellite radio or subscription radio (SR) is a digital radio signal that is broadcast by a communications satellite, which covers a much wider geographical range than terrestrial radio signals.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Amateur radio operators have access to amateur satellites, which have been designed specifically to carry amateur radio traffic.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Most such satellites operate as spaceborne repeaters, and are generally accessed by amateurs equipped with UHF or VHF radio equipment and highly directional antennas such as Yagis or dish antennas.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Due to launch costs, most current amateur satellites are launched into fairly low Earth orbits, and are designed to deal with only a limited number of brief contacts at any given time.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Some satellites also provide data-forwarding services using the X.25 or similar protocols.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] After the 1990s, satellite communication technology has been used as a means to connect to the Internet via broadband data connections.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] This can be very useful for users who are located in remote areas, and cannot access a broadband connection, or require high availability of services.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Communications satellites are used for military communications applications, such as Global Command and Control Systems.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Examples of military systems that use communication satellites are the MILSTAR, the DSCS, and the FLTSATCOM of the United States, NATO satellites, United Kingdom satellites (for instance Skynet), and satellites of the former Soviet Union.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] India has launched its first Military Communication satellite GSAT-7, its transponders operate in UHF, F, C and Ku band bands.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Typically military satellites operate in the UHF, SHF (also known as X-band) or EHF (also known as Ka band) frequency bands.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] Near-ground *in situ* environmental monitoring equipment (such as tide gauges, weather stations, weather buoys, and radiosondes), may use satellites for one-way data transmission or two-way telemetry and telecontrol.
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] It may be based on a secondary payload of a weather satellite (as in the case of GOES and METEOSAT and others in the Argos system) or in dedicated satellites (such as SCD).
[src:satellite-systems/communications-satellite] The data rate is typically much lower than in satellite Internet access.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] A **CubeSat** is a class of small satellite with a form factor of 10 cm (3.9 in) cubes.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSats have a mass of no more than 2 kg (4.4 lb) per unit, and often use commercial off-the-shelf (COTS) components for their electronics and structure.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSats are deployed into orbit from the International Space Station, or launched as secondary payloads on a launch vehicle.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] As of December 2023, more than 2,300 CubeSats have been launched.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Academia accounted for the majority of CubeSat launches until 2013, when more than half of launches were for non-academic purposes, and by 2014 most newly deployed CubeSats were for commercial or amateur projects.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Functions typically involve experiments that can be miniaturized or serve purposes such as Earth observation or amateur radio.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSats are employed to demonstrate spacecraft technologies intended for small satellites or that present questionable feasibility and are unlikely to justify the cost of a larger satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Scientific experiments with unproven underlying theory may also find themselves aboard CubeSats, because their low cost can justify higher risks.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Biological research payloads have been flown on several missions, with more planned.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Several missions to the Moon and beyond are planning to use CubeSats.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The first CubeSats in deep space were flown in the MarCO mission, where two CubeSats were launched towards Mars in May 2018 alongside the successful *InSight* mission.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Some CubeSats have become countries' first-ever satellites, launched either by universities, state-owned, or private companies.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The searchable *Nanosatellite and CubeSat Database* lists over 4,000 CubeSats that have been or are planned to be launched since 1998.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The CubeSat, as initially proposed, did not set out to become a standard; rather, it became a standard over time by a process of emergence.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The first CubeSats launched in June 2003 on a Russian Eurockot, and approximately 75 CubeSats had entered orbit by 2012.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Among that first group was CUTE-I, a 1 kg, 10 cm satellite developed by the Tokyo Institute of Technology Laboratory for Space Systems.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The need for such a small-factor satellite became apparent in 1998 as a result of work done at Stanford University's Space System Development Laboratory.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] At SSDL, students had been working on the OPAL (Orbiting Picosatellite Automatic Launcher) microsatellite since 1995.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] OPAL's mission to deploy daughter-ship "picosatellites" had resulted in the development of a launcher system that was "hopelessly complicated" and could only be made to work "most of the time".
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] With the project's delays mounting, Twiggs sought DARPA funding that resulted in the redesign of the launching mechanism into a simple pusher-plate concept with the satellites held in place by a spring-loaded door.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Desiring to shorten the development cycle experienced on OPAL and inspired by the picosatellites OPAL carried, Twiggs set out to find "how much could you reduce the size and still have a practical satellite".
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The picosatellites on OPAL were 10.1 cm × 7.6 cm × 2.5 cm (4 in × 3 in × 1 in), a size that was not conducive to covering all sides of the spacecraft with solar cells.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Inspired by a 4 in (10 cm) cubic plastic box used to display Beanie Babies in stores, Twiggs first settled on the larger ten-centimeter cube as a guideline for the new CubeSat concept.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] A model of a launcher was developed for the new satellite using the same pusher-plate concept that had been used in the modified OPAL launcher.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Twiggs presented the idea to Puig-Suari in the summer of 1999 and then at the Japan–U.S.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Science, Technology and Space Applications Program (JUSTSAP) conference in November 1999.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The term "CubeSat" was coined to denote nanosatellites that adhere to the standards described in the CubeSat design specification.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Cal Poly published the standard in an effort led by aerospace engineering professor Jordi Puig-Suari.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Bob Twiggs, of the Department of Aeronautics & Astronautics at Stanford University, and currently a member of the space science faculty at Morehead State University in Kentucky, has contributed to the CubeSat community.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] His efforts have focused on CubeSats from educational institutions.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The specification does not apply to other cube-like nanosatellites such as the NASA "MEPSI" nanosatellite, which is slightly larger than a CubeSat.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] GeneSat-1 was NASA's first fully automated, self-contained biological spaceflight experiment on a satellite of its size.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] It was also the first U.S.-launched CubeSat.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] This work, led by John Hines at NASA Ames Research, became the catalyst for the entire NASA CubeSat program.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] In 2017, this standardization effort led to the publication of ISO 17770:2017 by the International Organization for Standardization.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] This standard defines specifications for CubeSats including their physical, mechanical, electrical, and operational requirements.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] It also provides a specification for the interface between the CubeSat and its launch vehicle, which lists the capabilities required to survive the environmental conditions during and after launch and describes the standard deployment interface used to release the satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The development of standards shared by a large number of spacecraft contributes to a significant reduction in the development time and cost of CubeSat missions.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The CubeSat specification accomplishes several high-level goals.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The main reason for miniaturizing satellites is to reduce the cost of deployment: they are often suitable for launch in multiples, using the excess capacity of larger launch vehicles.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The CubeSat design specifically minimizes risk to the rest of the launch vehicle and payloads.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Encapsulation of the launcher–payload interface takes away the amount of work that would previously be required for mating a piggyback satellite with its launcher.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Unification among payloads and launchers enables quick exchanges of payloads and utilization of launch opportunities on short notice.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Standard CubeSats are made up of 10 cm × 10 cm × 11.35 cm (3.94 in × 3.94 in × 4.47 in) units designed to provide 10 cm × 10 cm × 10 cm (3.9 in × 3.9 in × 3.9 in) or 1 L (0.22 imp gal; 0.26 US gal) of useful volume, with each unit weighing no more than 2 kg (4.4 lb).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The smallest standard size is 1U, consisting of a single unit, while the most common form factor was the 3U, which comprised over 40% of all nanosatellites launched to date.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Larger form factors, such as the 6U and 12U, are composed of 3Us stacked side by side.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] In 2014, two 6U Perseus-M CubeSats were launched for maritime surveillance, the largest yet at the time.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The Mars Cube One (MarCO) mission in 2018 launched two 6U cubesats towards Mars.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Since nearly all CubeSats are 10 cm × 10 cm (3.9 in × 3.9 in) (regardless of length) they can all be launched and deployed using a common deployment system called a Poly-PicoSatellite Orbital Deployer (P-POD), developed and built by Cal Poly.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] No electronics form factors or communications protocols are specified or required by the CubeSat Design Specification, but COTS hardware has consistently used certain features which many treat as standards in CubeSat electronics.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Most COTS and custom designed electronics fit the form of PC/104, which was not designed for CubeSats but presents a 90 mm × 96 mm (3.5 in × 3.8 in) profile that allows most of the spacecraft's volume to be occupied.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Technically, the PCI-104 form is the variant of PC/104 used and the actual pinout used does not reflect the pinout specified in the PCI-104 standard.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Stackthrough connectors on the boards allow for simple assembly and electrical interfacing and most manufacturers of CubeSat electronics hardware hold to the same signal arrangement, but some products do not, so care must be taken to ensure consistent signal and power arrangements to prevent damage.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Care must be taken in electronics selection to ensure the devices can tolerate the radiation present.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] For very low Earth orbits (LEO) in which atmospheric reentry would occur in just days or weeks, radiation can largely be ignored and standard consumer grade electronics may be used.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Consumer electronic devices can survive LEO radiation for that time as the chance of a single event upset (SEU) is very low.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Spacecraft in a sustained low Earth orbit lasting months or years are at risk and only fly hardware designed for and tested in irradiated environments.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Missions beyond low Earth orbit or which would remain in low Earth orbit for many years must use radiation-hardened devices.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Further considerations are made for operation in high vacuum due to the effects of sublimation, outgassing, and metal whiskers, which may result in mission failure.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The number of joined units classifies the size of CubeSats and according to the CubeSat Design Specification are scalable along only one axis to fit the forms of 0.5U, 1U, 1.5U, 2U, or 3U.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] All the standard sizes of CubeSat have been built and launched, and represent the form factors for nearly all launched CubeSats as of 2015.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Materials used in the structure must feature the same coefficient of thermal expansion as the deployer to prevent jamming.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Specifically, allowed materials are four aluminum alloys: 7075, 6061, 5005, and 5052.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Aluminum used on the structure which contacts the P-POD must be anodized to prevent cold welding, and other materials may be used for the structure if a waiver is obtained.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Beyond cold welding, further consideration is put into material selection as not all materials can be used in vacuums.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Structures often feature soft dampers at each end, typically made of rubber, to lessen the effects of impacting other CubeSats in the P-POD.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Protrusions beyond the maximum dimensions are allowed by the standard specification, to a maximum of 6.5 mm (0.26 in) beyond each side.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Any protrusions may not interfere with the deployment rails and are typically occupied by antennas and solar panels.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] In Revision 13 of the CubeSat Design Specification an extra available volume was defined for use on 3U projects.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The additional volume is made possible by space typically wasted in the P-POD Mk III's spring mechanism.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] 3U CubeSats which utilize the space are designated 3U+ and may place components in a cylindrical volume centered on one end of the CubeSat.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The cylindrical space has a maximum diameter of 6.4 cm (2.5 in) and a height no greater than 3.6 cm (1.4 in) while not allowing for any increase in mass beyond the 3U's maximum of 4 kg (8.8 lb).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Propulsion systems and antennas are the most common components that might require the additional volume, though the payload sometimes extends into this volume.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Deviations from the dimension and mass requirements can be waived following application and negotiation with the launch service provider.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSat structures do not have all the same strength concerns as larger satellites do, as they have the added benefit of the deployer supporting them structurally during launch.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Still, some CubeSats will undergo vibration analysis or structural analysis to ensure that components unsupported by the P-POD remain structurally sound throughout the launch.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Despite rarely undergoing the analysis that larger satellites do, CubeSats rarely fail due to mechanical issues.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Like larger satellites, CubeSats often feature multiple computers handling different tasks in parallel including the attitude control (orientation), power management, payload operation, and primary control tasks.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] COTS attitude-control systems typically include their own computer, as do the power management systems.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Payloads must be able to interface with the primary computer to be useful, which sometimes requires the use of another small computer.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Still, the primary computer may be used for payload related tasks, which might include image processing, data analysis, and data compression.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Tasks which the primary computer typically handles include the delegation of tasks to the other computers, attitude control, calculations for orbital maneuvers, scheduling, and activation of active thermal control components.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSat computers are highly susceptible to radiation and builders will take special steps to ensure proper operation in the high radiation of space, such as the use of ECC RAM.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Some satellites may incorporate redundancy by implementing multiple primary computers; this could be done on valuable missions to lessen the risk of mission failure.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Consumer smartphones have been used for computing in some CubeSats, such as NASA's PhoneSats.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Attitude control (orientation) for CubeSats relies on miniaturizing technology without significant performance degradation.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Tumbling typically occurs as soon as a CubeSat is deployed, due to asymmetric deployment forces and bumping with other CubeSats.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Some CubeSats operate normally while tumbling, but those that require pointing in a certain direction or cannot operate safely while spinning, must be detumbled.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Systems that perform attitude determination and control include reaction wheels, magnetorquers, thrusters, star trackers, Sun sensors, Earth sensors, angular rate sensors, and GPS receivers and antennas.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Combinations of these systems are typically seen in order to take each method's advantages and mitigate their shortcomings.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Reaction wheels are commonly utilized for their ability to impart relatively large moments for any given energy input, but reaction wheel's utility is limited due to saturation, the point at which a wheel cannot spin faster.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Examples of CubeSat reaction wheels include the Maryland Aerospace MAI-101 and the Sinclair Interplanetary RW-0.03-4.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Reaction wheels can be desaturated with the use of thrusters or magnetorquers.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Thrusters can provide large moments by imparting a couple on the spacecraft but inefficiencies in small propulsion systems cause thrusters to run out of fuel rapidly.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Commonly found on nearly all CubeSats are magnetorquers which run electricity through a coil to take advantage of Earth's magnetic field to produce a turning moment.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Attitude-control modules and solar panels typically feature built-in magnetorquers.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] For CubeSats that only need to detumble, no attitude determination method beyond an angular rate sensor or electronic gyroscope is necessary.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Pointing in a specific direction is necessary for Earth observation, orbital maneuvers, maximizing solar power, and some scientific instruments.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Directional pointing accuracy can be achieved by sensing Earth and its horizon, the Sun, or specific stars.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Sinclair Interplanetary's SS-411 Sun sensor and ST-16 star tracker both have applications for CubeSats and have flight heritage.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Pumpkin's Colony I Bus uses an aerodynamic wing for passive attitude stabilization.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Determination of a CubeSat's location can be done through the use of on-board GPS, which is relatively expensive for a CubeSat, or by relaying radar tracking data to the craft from Earth-based tracking systems.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSat propulsion has made rapid advancements in: cold gas, chemical propulsion, electric propulsion, and solar sails.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The biggest challenge with CubeSat propulsion is preventing risk to the launch vehicle and its primary payload while still providing significant capability.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Components and methods that are commonly used in larger satellites are disallowed or limited, and the CubeSat Design Specification (CDS) requires a waiver for pressurization above 1.2 atm (120 kPa), over 100 Wh of stored chemical energy, and hazardous materials.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Those restrictions pose great challenges for CubeSat propulsion systems, as typical space propulsion systems utilize combinations of high pressures, high energy densities, and hazardous materials.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Beyond the restrictions set forth by launch service providers, various technical challenges further reduce the usefulness of CubeSat propulsion.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Gimbaled thrust cannot be used in small engines due to the complexity of gimbaling mechanisms, thrust vectoring must instead be achieved by thrusting asymmetrically in multiple-nozzle propulsion systems or by changing the center of mass relative to the CubeSat's geometry with actuated components.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Small motors may also not have room for throttling methods that allow smaller than fully on thrust, which is important for precision maneuvers such as rendezvous.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSats which require longer life also benefit from propulsion systems; when used for orbit keeping a propulsion system can slow orbital decay.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] A cold gas thruster typically stores inert gas, such as nitrogen, in a pressurized tank and releases the gas through a nozzle to produce thrust.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Operation is handled by just a single valve in most systems, which makes cold gas the simplest useful propulsion technology.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Cold gas propulsion systems can be very safe since the gases used do not have to be volatile or corrosive, though some systems opt to feature dangerous gases such as sulfur dioxide.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] This ability to use inert gases is highly advantageous to CubeSats as they are usually restricted from hazardous materials.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Only low performance can be achieved with them, preventing high impulse maneuvers even in low mass CubeSats.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Due to this low performance, their use in CubeSats for main propulsion is limited and designers choose higher efficiency systems with only minor increases in complexity.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Cold gas systems more often see use in CubeSat attitude control.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Chemical propulsion systems use a chemical reaction to produce a high-pressure, high-temperature gas that accelerates out of a nozzle.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Chemical propellant can be liquid, solid or a hybrid of both.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Liquid propellants can be a monopropellant passed through a catalyst, or bipropellant which combusts an oxidizer and a fuel.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The benefits of monopropellants are relatively low-complexity/high-thrust output, low power requirements, and high reliability.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Monopropellant motors tend to have high thrust while remaining comparatively simple, which also provides high reliability.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] These motors are practical for CubeSats due to their low power requirements and because their simplicity allows them to be very small.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Small hydrazine fueled motors have been developed, but may require a waiver to fly due to restrictions on hazardous chemicals set forth in the CubeSat Design Specification.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Safer chemical propellants which would not require hazardous chemical waivers are being developed, such as AF-M315 (hydroxylammonium nitrate) for which motors are being or have been designed.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] A "Water Electrolysis Thruster" is technically a chemical propulsion system, as it burns hydrogen and oxygen which it generates by on-orbit electrolysis of water.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSat electric propulsion typically uses electric energy to accelerate propellant to high speed, which results in high specific impulse.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Many of these technologies can be made small enough for use in nanosatellites, and several methods are in development.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Types of electric propulsion currently being designed for use in CubeSats include Hall-effect thrusters, ion thrusters, pulsed plasma thrusters, electrospray thrusters, and resistojets.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Several notable CubeSat missions plan to use electric propulsion, such as NASA's Lunar IceCube.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The high efficiency associated with electric propulsion could allow CubeSats to propel themselves to Mars.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Electric propulsion systems are disadvantaged in their use of power, which requires the CubeSat to have larger solar cells, more complicated power distribution, and often larger batteries.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Furthermore, many electric propulsion methods may still require pressurized tanks to store propellant, which is restricted by the CubeSat Design Specification.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The ESTCube-1 used an electric solar-wind sail, which relies on an electromagnetic field to act as a sail instead of a solid material.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] This technology used an electric field to deflect protons from solar wind to produce thrust.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] It is similar to an electrodynamic tether in that the craft only needs to supply electricity to operate.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Solar sails (also called light sails or photon sails) are a form of spacecraft propulsion using the radiation pressure (also called solar pressure) from stars to push large ultra-thin mirrors to high speeds, requiring no propellant.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Force from a solar sail scales with the sail's area, this makes sails well suited for use in CubeSats as their small mass results in the greater acceleration for a given solar sail's area.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] However, solar sails still need to be quite large compared to the satellite, which means useful solar sails must be deployed, adding mechanical complexity and a potential source of failure.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] This propulsion method is the only one not plagued with restrictions set by the CubeSat Design Specification, as it does not require high pressures, hazardous materials, or significant chemical energy.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] A small number of CubeSats have employed a solar sail as its main propulsion and stability in deep space, including the 3U NanoSail-D2 launched in 2010, and the LightSail-1 in May 2015.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] LightSail-2 successfully deployed on a Falcon Heavy rocket in 2019, while one CubeSat that was planned to launch on the Space Launch System's first flight (Artemis 1) in November 2022 was set to use a solar sail: the Near-Earth Asteroid Scout (NEA Scout).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The CubeSat was declared lost when communications were not established within 2 days.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSats use solar cells to convert solar light to electricity that is then stored in rechargeable lithium-ion batteries that provide power during eclipse as well as during peak load times.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] These satellites have a limited surface area on their external walls for solar cells assembly, and has to be effectively shared with other parts, such as antennas, optical sensors, camera lens, propulsion systems, and access ports.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Lithium-ion batteries feature high energy-to-mass ratios, making them well suited to use on mass-restricted spacecraft.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Battery charging and discharging is typically handled by a dedicated electrical power system (EPS).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Batteries sometimes feature heaters to prevent the battery from reaching dangerously low temperatures which might cause battery decay and mission failure.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The rate at which the batteries decay depends on the number of cycles for which they are charged and discharged, as well as the depth of each discharge: the greater the average depth of discharge, the faster a battery degrades.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] For LEO missions, the number of cycles of discharge can be expected to be on the order of several hundred.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Due to size and weight constraints, common CubeSats flying in LEO with body-mounted solar panels have generated less than 10 W.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Recent innovations include additional spring-loaded solar arrays that deploy as soon as the satellite is released, as well as arrays that feature thermal knife mechanisms that would deploy the panels when commanded.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSats may not be powered between launch and deployment, and must feature a remove-before-flight pin which cuts all power to prevent operation during loading into the P-POD.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Additionally, a deployment switch is actuated while the craft is loaded into a P-POD, cutting power to the spacecraft and is deactivated after exiting the P-POD.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The low cost of CubeSats has enabled unprecedented access to space for smaller institutions and organizations but, for most CubeSat forms, the range and available power is limited to about 2 W for its communications antennae.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Because of tumbling and low power range, radio-communications are a challenge.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Many CubeSats use an omnidirectional monopole or dipole antenna built with commercial measuring tape.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] For more demanding needs, some companies offer high-gain antennae for CubeSats, but their deployment and pointing systems are significantly more complex.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] For example, MIT and JPL are developing an inflatable dish antenna based on a mylar skin inflated with a sublimating powder, claiming a 7× boost in range—potentially able to reach the Moon—but questions linger concerning survivability after micrometeor impacts.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] JPL has successfully developed X-band and Ka-band high-gain antennas for MarCO and Radar in a CubeSat (RaInCube) missions.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Traditionally, Low Earth Orbit Cubesats use antennas for communication purpose at UHF and S-band.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] To venture farther in the Solar System, larger antennas compatible with the Deep Space Network (X-band and Ka-band) are required.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] JPL's engineers developed several deployable high-gain antennas compatible with 6U-class CubeSats for MarCO and Near-Earth Asteroid Scout.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] JPL's engineers have also developed a 0.5 m (1 ft 8 in) mesh reflector antenna operating at Ka-band and compatible with the DSN that folds in a 1.5U stowage volume.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] For MarCO, JPL's antenna engineers designed a Folded Panel Reflectarray (FPR) to fit on a 6U CubeSat bus and supports X-band Mars-to-Earth telecommunications at 8 kbit/s at 1AU.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Different CubeSat components possess different acceptable temperature ranges, beyond which they may become temporarily or permanently inoperable.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Satellites in orbit are heated by radiative heat emitted from the Sun directly and reflected off Earth, as well as heat generated by the craft's components.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSats must also cool by radiating heat either into space or into the cooler Earth's surface, if it is cooler than the spacecraft.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] All of these radiative heat sources and sinks are rather constant and very predictable, so long as the CubeSat's orbit and eclipse time are known.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Components used to ensure the temperature requirements are met in CubeSats include multi-layer insulation and heaters for the battery.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Other spacecraft thermal control techniques in small satellites include specific component placement based on expected thermal output of those components and, rarely, deployed thermal devices such as louvers.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Analysis and simulation of the spacecraft's thermal model is an important determining factor in applying thermal management components and techniques.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSats with special thermal concerns, often associated with certain deployment mechanisms and payloads, may be tested in a thermal vacuum chamber before launch.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Such testing provides a larger degree of assurance than full-sized satellites can receive, since CubeSats are small enough to fit inside of a thermal vacuum chamber in their entirety.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Temperature sensors are typically placed on different CubeSat components so that action may be taken to avoid dangerous temperature ranges, such as reorienting the craft in order to avoid or introduce direct thermal radiation to a specific part, thereby allowing it to cool or heat.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] CubeSat forms a cost-effective independent means of getting a payload into orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] After delays from low-cost launchers such as Interorbital Systems, launch prices have been about $100,000 per unit, but newer operators are offering lower pricing.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] A typical price to launch a 1U cubesat with a full service contract (including end-to-end integration, licensing, transportation etc.) was about $60,000 in 2021.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Some CubeSats have complicated components or instruments, such as LightSail-1, that push their construction cost into the millions of dollars, but a basic 1U CubeSat can cost about $50,000 to construct.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] This makes CubeSats a viable option for some schools, universities, and small businesses.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The *Nanosatellite & Cubesat Database* lists over 2,000 CubeSats that have been launched since 1998.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] One of the earliest CubeSat launches was on 30 June 2003 from Plesetsk, Russia, with Eurockot Launch Services's *Multiple Orbit Mission*.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The CubeSats were injected into a Sun-synchronous orbit and included the Danish AAU CubeSat and DTUSat, the Japanese XI-IV and CUTE-1, the Canadian Can X-1, and the US Quakesat.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] On February 13, 2012, three P-POD deployers containing seven CubeSats were placed into orbit along with the Lares satellite aboard a Vega rocket launched from French Guiana.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The CubeSats were launched in the framework of the "Vega Maiden Flight" opportunity of the European Space Agency.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] On September 13, 2012, eleven CubeSats were launched from eight P-PODs, as part of the "OutSat" secondary payload aboard a United Launch Alliance Atlas V rocket.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] This was the largest number of CubeSats (and largest volume of 24U) orbited on a single launch so far, made possible by the new NPS CubeSat Launcher system (NPSCuL) developed at the Naval Postgraduate School (NPS).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The CubeSats were: SMDC-ONE 2.2 (Baker), SMDC-ONE 2.1 (Able), AeroCube 4.0(x3), Aeneas, CSSWE, CP5, CXBN, CINEMA, and Re (STARE).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Five CubeSats (Raiko, Niwaka, We-Wish, TechEdSat, F-1) were placed into orbit from the International Space Station on October 4, 2012, as a technology demonstration of small satellite deployment from the ISS.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] They were launched and delivered to ISS as a cargo of Kounotori 3, and an ISS astronaut prepared the deployment mechanism attached to Japanese Experiment Module's robotic arm.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Four CubeSats were deployed from the Cygnus Mass Simulator, which was launched April 21, 2013 on the maiden flight of Orbital Sciences' Antares rocket.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Three of them are 1U PhoneSats built by NASA's Ames Research Center to demonstrate the use of smart phones as avionics in CubeSats.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The fourth was a 3U satellite, called Dove-1, built by Planet Labs.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] On April 26, 2013 NEE-01 Pegaso was launched and was the first CubeSat able to transmit live video from orbit, also the first 1U CubeSat to achieve more than 100 watts of power as installed capacity.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Later in November same year NEE-02 Krysaor also transmitted live video from orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Both CubeSats were built by the Ecuadorian Space Agency.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] A total of thirty-three CubeSats were deployed from the ISS on February 11, 2014.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Of those thirty-three, twenty-eight were part of the Flock-1 constellation of Earth-imaging CubeSats.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Of the other five, two are from other US-based companies, two from Lithuania, and one from Peru.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The LightSail-1 is a 3U CubeSat prototype propelled by a solar sail.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] It was launched on 20 May 2015 from Florida.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Its four sails are made of very thin Mylar and have a total area of 32 m2 (340 sq ft).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] This test will allow a full checkout of the satellite's systems in advance of the main 2016 mission.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] On October 5, 2015, AAUSAT5 (Aalborg University, Denmark), was deployed from the ISS. launched in the framework of the "Fly Your Satellite!" programme of the European Space Agency.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The Miniature X-ray Solar Spectrometer CubeSat is a 3U launched to the International Space Station on 6 December 2015 from where it was deployed on 16 May 2016.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] It is the first mission launched in the NASA Science Mission Directorate CubeSat Integration Panel, which is focused on doing science with CubeSats.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] As of 12 July 2016, the minimum mission success criterion (one month of science observations) has been met, but the spacecraft continues to perform nominally and observations continue.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Three CubeSats were launched on April 25, 2016, together with Sentinel-1B on a Soyuz rocket VS14 launched from Kourou, French Guiana.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The satellites were: AAUSAT4 (Aalborg University, Denmark), e-st@r-II (Politecnico di Torino, Italy) and OUFTI-1 (Université de Liège, Belgium).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The CubeSats were launched in the framework of the "Fly Your Satellite!" programme of the European Space Agency.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] On February 15, 2017, Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) set a record with the launch of 104 satellites on a single rocket.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The launch of PSLV-C37 in a single payload, including the Cartosat-2 series and 103 co-passenger satellites, together weighed over 650 kg (1,430 lb).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Of the 104 satellites, all but three were CubeSats.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Of the 101 nano satellites, 96 were from the United States and one each from Israel, Kazakhstan, the Netherlands, Switzerland and the United Arab Emirates.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The May 2018 launch of the *InSight* stationary Mars lander included two CubeSats to fly by Mars to provide additional relay communications from *InSight* to Earth during entry and landing.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] This is the first flight of CubeSats outside of the Earth's direct orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The mission CubeSat technology is called Mars Cube One (MarCO); each one is a six-unit CubeSat, 14.4 in × 9.5 in × 4.6 in (37 cm × 24 cm × 12 cm).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] MarCO is an experiment, but not necessary for the *InSight* mission, to add relay communications to space missions in important time durations, in this case from the time of *InSight* atmospheric entry to its landing.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] MarCO launched in May 2018 with the *InSight* lander, separated after launch and then traveled in their own trajectories to Mars.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] After separation, both MarCO spacecraft deployed two radio antennas and two solar panels.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The high-gain, X band antenna is a flat panel to direct radio waves.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] MarCO navigated to Mars independently from the *InSight* lander, making their own course adjustments on the flight.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] During *InSight*'s entry, descent and landing (EDL) in November 2018, the lander transmitted telemetry in the UHF radio band to NASA's Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter (MRO) flying overhead.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] MRO forwarded EDL information to Earth using a radio frequency in the X band, but cannot simultaneously receive information in one band if transmitting on another.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Confirmation of a successful landing could be received on Earth several hours after, so MarCO was a technology demonstration of real-time telemetry during the landing.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The Interplanetary Nano-Spacecraft Pathfinder in Relevant Environment (INSPIRE) is a planned NASA mission that will send CubeSats out of Earth’s orbit and into deep space.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] INSPIRE aims to demonstrate that CubeSats can operate, communicate, and be navigated outside of Earth’s orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The launch date of this mission is not yet determined.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] NASA's CubeSat Launch Initiative created in 2010, provides CubeSat launch opportunities to educational institutions, non-profit organizations and NASA Centers.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] As of 2016 the CubeSat Launch Initiative had launched 46 CubeSats flown on 12 ELaNa Missions from 28 unique organizations and has selected 119 CubeSat missions from 66 unique organizations.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Educational Launch of Nanosatellites (ELaNa) missions have included: BisonSat the first CubeSat built by a tribal college, TJ3Sat the first CubeSat built by a high school and STMSat-1 the first CubeSat built by an elementary school.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] NASA releases an Announcement of Opportunity in August of each year with selections made the following February.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] NASA initiated the Cube Quest Challenge in 2015, a competition to foster innovation in the use of CubeSats beyond low Earth orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The Cube Quest Challenge offered $5 million to teams that met the challenge objectives of designing, building and delivering flight-qualified, small satellites capable of advanced operations near and beyond the Moon.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Teams competed for a variety of prizes in lunar orbit or deep space.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] 10 CubeSats from different teams were launched to cislunar space as secondary payloads on board the Artemis 1 in 2022.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] "Fly Your Satellite!" is the ongoing CubeSats programme of the Education Office of the European Space Agency.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] University students have the opportunity to develop and implement their CubeSat mission with support of ESA specialists.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Participating student teams can experience the full cycle from designing, building, and testing to eventually, the possibility of launching and operating their CubeSat.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The fourth iteration of the Fly Your Satellite! programme closed a call for proposals in February 2022.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The Canadian Space Agency announced the Canadian CubeSat Project (CCP) in 2017, and the participating teams were selected in May of 2018.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The programme provides funding and support to one university or college in each province and territory to develop a CubeSat for launch from the ISS.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The objective of the CCP is to provide students with direct hands on experience in the space industry, while preparing them to enter into a career in the space domain.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] QB50 is a proposed international network of 50 CubeSats for multi-point, *in-situ* measurements in the lower thermosphere (90–350 km) and re-entry research.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] QB50 is an initiative of the Von Karman Institute and is funded by the European Commission as part of the 7th Framework Programme (FP7).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Double-unit (2U) CubeSats (10×10×20 cm) are developed, with one unit (the 'functional' unit) providing the usual satellite functions and the other unit (the 'science' unit) accommodating a set of standardised sensors for lower thermosphere and re-entry research.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] 35 CubeSats are envisaged to be provided by universities from 22 countries around the world, among them 4 are from the US, 4 from China, 4 from France, 3 from Australia and 3 from South Korea.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Ten 2U or 3U CubeSats are foreseen to serve for in-orbit technology demonstration of new space technologies.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The Request for Proposals (RFP) for the QB50 CubeSat was released on February 15, 2012.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Two "precursor" QB50 satellites were launched aboard a Dnepr rocket on June 19, 2014.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] All 50 CubeSats were supposed to be launched together on a single Cyclone-4 launch vehicle in February 2016, but due to the unavailability of the launch vehicle, 36 satellites were launched aboard Cygnus CRS OA-7 on 18 April 2017 and subsequently deployed from the ISS.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] A dozen other CubeSats were manifested on the PSLV-XL C38 mission in May 2017.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Unlike full-sized spacecraft, CubeSats can be delivered as cargo to, and deployed by, the International Space Station.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] This presents an alternative method of achieving orbit apart from deployment by a launch vehicle.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] NanoRacks and Made in Space are developing means of constructing CubeSats on the International Space Station.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] NASA's CubeSat Launch Initiative launched more than 46 CubeSats on its ELaNa missions over the several years prior to 2016, and 57 were planned for flight over the next several years.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] No matter how inexpensive or versatile CubeSats may be, they must hitch rides as secondary payloads on large rockets launching much larger spacecraft, at prices starting around $100,000 as of 2015.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Since CubeSats are deployed by P-PODs and similar deployment systems, they can be integrated and launched into virtually any launch vehicle.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] However, some launch service providers refuse to launch CubeSats, whether on all launches or only on specific launches, two examples as of 2015 were ILS and Sea Launch.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] SpaceX, Exolaunch, and Space BD are three recent companies that offer commercial launch services for CubeSats as secondary payload, but a launch backlog still exists.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Additionally, India's ISRO has been commercially launching foreign CubeSats since 2009 as secondary payloads.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] On 15 Feb 2017, ISRO set the world record by launching 103 CubeSats on board its Polar Satellite Launch Vehicle for various foreign companies.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] ISC Kosmotras and Eurockot also offer launch services for CubeSats.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] SpaceX beat the record in 2021 with the Transporter-1 (spaceflight) carrying 143 spacecraft to orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Rocket Lab specializes in launching CubeSats on its Electron from New Zealand.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] On 5 May 2015, NASA announced a program based at the Kennedy Space Center to develop a class of rockets designed to launch very small satellites: the NASA Venture Class Launch Services (VCLS), which will offer a payload mass of 30 kg to 60 kg for each launcher.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Five months later, in October 2015, NASA awarded a total of $17.1 million to three separate startup launch companies for one flight each: $6.9 million to Rocket Lab (Electron rocket); $5.5 million to Firefly Space Systems (Alpha rocket); and $4.7 million to Virgin Galactic (LauncherOne rocket).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The payloads for the three flights under the VCLS contract have not yet been assigned.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Other small satellite launch systems are under development that would carry CubeSats alongside a small payload, including the *Neptune* series of rockets by Interorbital Systems, Garvey Spacecraft's *Nanosat Launch Vehicle*, and the SPARK rocket.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] In addition to conventional launch vehicles and facilitators like KSF Space, several air launch to orbit vehicles are in the works by Generation Orbit Launch Services and Boeing (in the form of their Small Launch Vehicle).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Many aspects of CubeSats such as structure, propulsion, material, computing and telecommunications, power, and additional specific instruments or measurement devices pose challenges to the use of CubeSat technology beyond Earth's orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The launch date was expected to be 2014, but has yet to occur and the date is listed by NASA as TBD.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] P-PODs (Poly-PicoSatellite Orbital Deployers) were designed with CubeSats to provide a common platform for secondary payloads.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] P-PODs are mounted to a launch vehicle and carry CubeSats into orbit and deploy them once the proper signal is received from the launch vehicle.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] The P-POD Mk III has capacity for three 1U CubeSats, or other 0.5U, 1U, 1.5U, 2U, or 3U CubeSats combination up to a maximum volume of 3U.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Other CubeSat deployers exist, with the NanoRacks CubeSat Deployer (NRCSD) on the International Space Station being the most popular method of CubeSat deployment as of 2014.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] While the P-POD is limited to launching a 3U CubeSat at most, the NRCSD can launch a 6U (10 cm × 10 cm × 68.1 cm (3.9 in × 3.9 in × 26.8 in)) CubeSat and the ISIPOD can launch a different form of 6U CubeSat (10 cm × 22.63 cm × 34.05 cm (3.94 in × 8.91 in × 13.41 in)).
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] While nearly all CubeSats are deployed from a launch vehicle or the International Space Station, some are deployed by the primary payloads themselves.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] For example, FASTSAT deployed the NanoSail-D2, a 3U CubeSat.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] This was done again with the Cygnus Mass Simulator as the primary payload launched on the maiden flight of the Antares rocket, carrying and later deploying four CubeSats.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] For CubeSat applications beyond Earth's orbit, the method of deploying the satellites from the primary payload will also be adopted.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Ten CubeSats were launched on the Artemis 1, placing them in the vicinity of the Moon.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] InSight, a Mars lander, also sent CubeSats beyond Earth orbit to use them as relay communications satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Known as MarCO A and B, they are the first CubeSats sent beyond the Earth–Moon system.
[src:satellite-systems/cubesat] Chasqui I saw a unique deployment process, when it was deployed by hand during a spacewalk on the International Space Station in 2014.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] A **geostationary orbit**, also referred to as a **GEO** or **GSO**, is a circular geosynchronous orbit 35,786 km (22,236 mi) in altitude above Earth's equator, 42,164 km (26,199 mi) in radius from Earth's center, and following the direction of Earth's rotation.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] An object in such an orbit has an orbital period equal to Earth's rotational period, one sidereal day, and so to ground observers it appears motionless, in a fixed position in the sky.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The concept of a geostationary orbit was popularised by the science fiction writer Arthur C.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Clarke in the 1940s as a way to revolutionise telecommunications, and the first satellite to be placed in this kind of orbit was launched in 1963.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Communications satellites are often placed in a geostationary orbit so that Earth-based satellite antennas do not have to rotate to track them but can be pointed permanently at the position in the sky where the satellites are located.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Weather satellites are also placed in this orbit for real-time monitoring and data collection, as are navigation satellites in order to provide a known calibration point and enhance GPS accuracy.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Geostationary satellites are launched via a temporary orbit, and then placed in a "slot" above a particular point on the Earth's surface.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The satellite requires periodic station-keeping to maintain its position.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Modern retired geostationary satellites are placed in a higher graveyard orbit to avoid collisions.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] In 1928, Herman Potočnik described both geosynchronous orbits in general and the special case of the geostationary Earth orbit in particular as useful orbits for space stations.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The first appearance of a geostationary orbit in popular literature was in October 1942, in the first Venus Equilateral story by George O.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Smith, but Smith did not go into details.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] British science fiction author Arthur C.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Clarke popularised and expanded the concept in a 1945 paper entitled *Extra-Terrestrial Relays – Can Rocket Stations Give Worldwide Radio Coverage?*, published in *Wireless World* magazine.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Clarke acknowledged the connection in his introduction to *The Complete Venus Equilateral*.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The orbit, which Clarke first described as useful for broadcast and relay communications satellites, is sometimes called the Clarke orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Similarly, the collection of artificial satellites in this orbit is known as the Clarke Belt.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] In technical terminology the orbit is referred to as either a geostationary or geosynchronous equatorial orbit, with the terms used somewhat interchangeably.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The first geostationary satellite was designed by Harold Rosen while he was working at Hughes Aircraft in 1959.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Inspired by Sputnik 1, he wanted to use a geostationary satellite to globalise communications.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Telecommunications between the US and Europe was then possible between just 136 people at a time, and reliant on high frequency radios and an undersea cable.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Conventional wisdom at the time was that it would require too much rocket power to place a satellite in a geostationary orbit and it would not survive long enough to justify the expense, so early efforts were put towards constellations of satellites in low or medium Earth orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The first of these were the passive Echo balloon satellites in 1960, followed by Telstar 1 in 1962.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Although these projects had difficulties with signal strength and tracking, issues that could be solved using geostationary orbits, the concept was seen as impractical, so Hughes often withheld funds and support.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] By 1961, Rosen and his team had produced a cylindrical prototype with a diameter of 76 centimetres (30 in), height of 38 centimetres (15 in), weighing 11.3 kilograms (25 lb), light and small enough to be placed into orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] It was spin stabilised with a dipole antenna producing a pancake shaped beam.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] In August 1961, they were contracted to begin building the real satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] They lost Syncom 1 to electronics failure, but Syncom 2 was successfully placed into a geosynchronous orbit in 1963.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Although its inclined orbit still required moving antennas, it was able to relay TV transmissions, and allowed for US President John F.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Kennedy in Washington D.C., to phone Nigerian prime minister Abubakar Tafawa Balewa aboard the USNS Kingsport docked in Lagos on August 23, 1963.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The first satellite placed in a geostationary orbit was Syncom 3, which was launched by a Delta D rocket in 1964.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] With its increased bandwidth, this satellite was able to transmit live coverage of the Summer Olympics from Japan to America.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Geostationary orbits have been in common use ever since, in particular for satellite television.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Today there are hundreds of geostationary satellites providing remote sensing and communications.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Most commercial communications satellites, broadcast satellites and SBAS satellites operate in geostationary orbits.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Geostationary communication satellites are useful because they are visible from a large area of the earth's surface, extending 81° away in latitude and 77° in longitude.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] They appear stationary in the sky, which eliminates the need for ground stations to have movable antennas.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] This means that Earth-based observers can erect small, cheap and stationary antennas that are always directed at the desired satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] However, latency becomes significant as it takes about 240 ms for a signal to pass from a ground based transmitter on the equator to the satellite and back again.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] This delay presents problems for latency-sensitive applications such as voice communication, so geostationary communication satellites are primarily used for unidirectional entertainment and applications where low latency alternatives are not available.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Geostationary satellites are directly overhead at the equator and appear lower in the sky to an observer nearer the poles.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] As the observer's latitude increases, communication becomes more difficult due to factors such as atmospheric refraction, Earth's thermal emission, line-of-sight obstructions, and signal reflections from the ground or nearby structures.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] At latitudes above about 81°, geostationary satellites are below the horizon and cannot be seen at all.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Because of this, some Russian communication satellites have used elliptical Molniya and Tundra orbits, which have excellent visibility at high latitudes.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] A worldwide network of operational geostationary meteorological satellites is used to provide visible and infrared images of Earth's surface and atmosphere for weather observation, oceanography, and atmospheric tracking.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] As of 2019 there are 19 satellites in either operation or stand-by.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] These satellites typically capture images in the visual and infrared spectrum with a spatial resolution between 0.5 and 4 square kilometres.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The coverage is typically 70°, and in some cases less.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Geostationary satellite imagery has been used for tracking volcanic ash, measuring cloud top temperatures and water vapour, oceanography, measuring land temperature and vegetation coverage, facilitating cyclone path prediction, and providing real time cloud coverage and other tracking data.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Some information has been incorporated into meteorological prediction models, but due to their wide field of view, full-time monitoring and lower resolution, geostationary weather satellite images are primarily used for short-term and real-time forecasting.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Geostationary satellites can be used to augment GNSS systems by relaying clock, ephemeris and ionospheric error corrections (calculated from ground stations of a known position) and providing an additional reference signal.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] This improves position accuracy from approximately 5m to 1m or less.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Geostationary satellites are launched to the east into a prograde orbit that matches the rotation rate of the equator.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The smallest inclination that a satellite can be launched into is that of the launch site's latitude, so launching the satellite from close to the equator limits the amount of inclination change needed later.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Additionally, launching from close to the equator allows the speed of the Earth's rotation to give the satellite a boost.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] A launch site should have water or deserts to the east, so any failed rockets do not fall on a populated area.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Most launch vehicles place geostationary satellites directly into a geostationary transfer orbit (GTO), an elliptical orbit with an apogee at GEO height and a low perigee.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] On-board satellite propulsion is then used to raise the perigee, circularise and reach GEO.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Satellites in geostationary orbit must all occupy a single ring above the equator.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The requirement to space these satellites apart, to avoid harmful radio-frequency interference during operations, means that there are a limited number of orbital slots available, and thus only a limited number of satellites can be operated in geostationary orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] This has led to conflict between different countries wishing access to the same orbital slots (countries near the same longitude but differing latitudes) and radio frequencies.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] These disputes are addressed through the International Telecommunication Union's allocation mechanism under the Radio Regulations.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] In the 1976 Bogota Declaration, eight countries located on the Earth's equator claimed sovereignty over the geostationary orbits above their territory, but the claims gained no international recognition.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Geostationary satellites require some station keeping to keep their position, and once they run out of thruster fuel they are generally retired.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The transponders and other onboard systems often outlive the thruster fuel and by allowing the satellite to move naturally into an inclined geosynchronous orbit some satellites can remain in use, or else be elevated to a graveyard orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] This process is becoming increasingly regulated and satellites must have a 90% chance of moving over 200 km above the geostationary belt at end of life.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Space debris at geostationary orbits typically has a lower collision speed than at low Earth orbit (LEO) since all GEO satellites orbit in the same plane, altitude and speed; however, the presence of satellites in eccentric orbits allows for collisions at up to 4 km/s (14,400 km/h; 8,900 mph).
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Although a collision is comparatively unlikely, GEO satellites have a limited ability to avoid any debris.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] At geosynchronous altitude, objects less than 10 cm in diameter cannot be seen from the Earth, making it difficult to assess their prevalence.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Despite efforts to reduce risk, spacecraft collisions have occurred.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] In 2017, both AMC-9 and Telkom-1 broke apart from an unknown cause.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] An inclination of zero ensures that the orbit remains over the equator at all times, making it stationary with respect to latitude from the point of view of a ground observer (and in the Earth-centered Earth-fixed reference frame).
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The orbital period is equal to exactly one sidereal day.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] This means that the satellite will return to the same point above the Earth's surface every (sidereal) day, regardless of other orbital properties.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] For a geostationary orbit in particular, it ensures that it holds the same longitude over time.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The eccentricity is zero, which produces a circular orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] This ensures that the satellite does not move closer or further away from the Earth, which would cause it to track backwards and forwards across the sky.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] A geostationary orbit can be achieved only at an altitude very close to 35,786 kilometres (22,236 miles) and directly above the equator.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] This equates to an orbital speed of 3.07 kilometres per second (1.91 miles per second) and an orbital period of 1,436 minutes, one sidereal day.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] This ensures that the satellite will match the Earth's rotational period and has a stationary footprint on the ground.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] All geostationary satellites have to be located on this ring.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] To correct for this perturbation, regular orbital stationkeeping maneuvers are necessary, amounting to a delta-v of approximately 50 m/s per year.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] A second effect to be taken into account is the longitudinal drift, caused by the asymmetry of the Earth – the equator is slightly elliptical (equatorial eccentricity).
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] There are two stable equilibrium points sometimes called "gravitational wells" (at 75.3°E and 108°W) and two corresponding unstable points (at 165.3°E and 14.7°W).
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Any geostationary object placed between the equilibrium points would (without any action) be slowly accelerated towards the stable equilibrium position, causing a periodic longitude variation.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The correction of this effect requires station-keeping maneuvers with a maximal delta-v of about 2 m/s per year, depending on the desired longitude.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Solar wind and radiation pressure also exert small forces on satellites: over time, these cause them to slowly drift away from their prescribed orbits.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] In the absence of servicing missions from the Earth or a renewable propulsion method, the consumption of thruster propellant for station-keeping places a limitation on the lifetime of the satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Hall-effect thrusters, which are currently in use, have the potential to prolong the service life of a satellite by providing high-efficiency electric propulsion.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] where *F*g is the gravitational force acting between two objects, *M*E is the mass of the Earth, 5.9736×1024 kg, *m*s is the mass of the satellite, *r* is the distance between the centers of their masses, and *G* is the gravitational constant, (6.67428±0.00067)×10−11 m3 kg−1 s−2.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] where *v* is the magnitude of the velocity (i.e. the speed) of the satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] where *T* is the orbital period (i.e. one sidereal day), and is equal to 86164.09054 s.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The product *GM*E is known with much greater precision than either factor alone; it is known as the geocentric gravitational constant *μ* = 398600.4418±0.0008 km3 s−2.
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The resulting orbital radius is 42,164 kilometres (26,199 miles).
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Subtracting the Earth's equatorial radius, 6,378 kilometres (3,963 miles), gives the altitude of 35,786 kilometres (22,236 miles).
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] By the same method, we can determine the orbital altitude for any similar pair of bodies, including the areostationary orbit of an object in relation to Mars, if it is assumed that it is spherical (which it is not entirely).
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] The gravitational constant *GM* (*μ*) for Mars has the value of 42830 km3 s−2, its equatorial radius is 3389.50 km and the known rotational period (*T*) of the planet is 1.02595676 Earth days (88642.66 s).
[src:satellite-systems/geostationary-orbit] Using these values, Mars' orbital altitude is equal to 17039 km.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] A **reaction wheel** (**RW**) is an electric motor attached to a flywheel, which, when its rotation speed is changed, causes a counter-rotation proportionately through conservation of angular momentum.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] A reaction wheel can rotate only around its center of mass; it is not capable of moving from one place to another (translational force).
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Reaction wheels are used primarily by spacecraft for three-axis fine attitude control, but can also be used for fast detumbling.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Reaction wheels do not require rockets or external applicators of torque, which reduces the mass fraction needed for fuel.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] They provide a high pointing accuracy, and are particularly useful when the spacecraft must be rotated by very small amounts, such as keeping a telescope pointed at a star.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] A reaction wheel is sometimes operated at a constant (or near-constant) rotation speed, to provide a satellite with a large amount of stored angular momentum.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] This has the effect of tending to stabilize that spacecraft axis to point in a nearly-fixed direction, allowing for a less-complicated attitude control system.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Satellites using this "momentum-bias" stabilization approach include SCISAT-1; by orienting the momentum wheel's axis to be parallel to the orbit-normal vector, this satellite is in a "pitch momentum bias" configuration.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Reaction wheels can also be used during the detumbling phase to stabilize the spacecraft after launcher separation or an unforeseen event.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] For three-axis control, reaction wheels must be mounted along at least three directions, with extra wheels providing redundancy to the attitude control system.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] A redundant mounting configuration could consist of four wheels along tetrahedral axes, or a spare wheel carried in addition to a three axis configuration.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Changes in speed (in either direction) are controlled electronically by computer.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] The strength of the materials used in a reaction wheel determine the speed at which the wheel would come apart, and therefore how much angular momentum it can store.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Since the reaction wheel is a small fraction of the spacecraft's total mass, easily controlled, temporary changes in its speed result in small changes in angle.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] The wheels therefore permit very precise changes in a spacecraft's attitude.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] For this reason, reaction wheels are often used to aim spacecraft carrying cameras or telescopes.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Over time, reaction wheels may build up enough stored momentum to exceed the maximum speed of the wheel, called saturation.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] However, slowing down the wheels imparts a torque causing undesired rotation.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Designers therefore supplement reaction wheel systems with other attitude control mechanisms to cancel out the torque caused by "desaturating" the reaction wheels.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Typically designers use "reaction control systems": arrays of small chemical rocket engines that fire as the wheels slow down to counter the torque the wheels are imparting on the spacecraft as they slow down.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] More fuel efficient methods for reaction wheel desaturation have been developed over time.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] By reducing the amount of fuel the spacecraft needs to be launched with, they increase the useful payload that can be delivered to orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] These methods include magnetorquers (better known as torque rods), which transfer angular momentum to the Earth through its planetary magnetic field requiring only electrical power and no fuel.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] They are however limited to areas of space with a sufficiently large magnetic field (such as in low Earth orbit).
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] In the absence of a sufficiently strong magnetic field, the next most efficient practice is to use high-efficiency attitude jets such as ion thrusters.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Beresheet was launched on a Falcon 9 rocket on 22 February 2019 1:45 UTC, with the goal of landing on the Moon.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Beresheet uses the low-energy transfer technique to save fuel.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Since its fourth maneuver in its elliptical orbit, to prevent shakes when the amount of liquid fuel ran low, there was a need to use a reaction wheel.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] The James Webb Space Telescope has six reaction wheels built by Rockwell Collins Deutschland.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] LightSail 2 was launched on 25 June 2019, focused around the concept of a solar sail.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] LightSail 2 uses a reaction wheel system to change orientation by very small amounts, allowing it to receive different amounts of momentum from the light across the sail, resulting in a higher altitude.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] The failure of one or more reaction wheels can cause a spacecraft to lose its ability to maintain attitude (orientation) and thus potentially cause a mission failure.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Recent studies conclude that these failures can be correlated with space weather effects.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] These events probably caused failures by inducing electrostatic discharge in the steel ball bearings of Ithaco wheels, compromising the smoothness of the mechanism.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Supporting this hypothesis, newer reaction wheels have non-conducting ceramic bearings, and none have failed in this manner.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Two servicing missions to the Hubble Space Telescope have replaced a reaction wheel.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] In February 1997, the Second Servicing Mission (STS-82) replaced one after 'electrical anomalies', rather than any mechanical problem.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Study of the returned mechanism provided a rare opportunity to study equipment that had undergone long-term service (seven years) in space, particularly for the effects of vacuum on lubricants.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] The lubricating compound was found to be in 'excellent condition'.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] In 2002, during Servicing Mission 3B (STS-109), astronauts from the shuttle *Columbia* replaced another reaction wheel.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Neither of these wheels had failed and Hubble was designed with four redundant wheels, and maintained pointing ability so long as three were functional.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] In 2004, during the mission of the *Hayabusa* spacecraft, an X-axis reaction wheel failed.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] The Y-axis wheel failed in 2005, causing the craft to rely on chemical thrusters to maintain attitude control.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] From July 2012 to May 11, 2013, two out of the four reaction wheels in the Kepler space telescope failed.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] This loss severely affected Kepler's ability to maintain a sufficiently precise orientation to continue its original mission.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] On August 15, 2013, engineers concluded that Kepler's reaction wheels cannot be recovered and that planet-searching using the transit method (measuring changes in star brightness caused by orbiting planets) could not continue.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Although the failed reaction wheels still function, they are experiencing friction exceeding acceptable levels, and consequently hindering the ability of the telescope to properly orient itself.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] On May 16, 2014, NASA extended the Kepler mission to a new mission named K2, which uses Kepler differently, but allows it to continue searching for exoplanets.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] On October 30, 2018, NASA announced the end of the Kepler mission after it was determined that the fuel supply had been exhausted.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] The NASA space probe *Dawn* had excess friction in one reaction wheel in June 2010.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] The loss of the reaction wheels limited the camera observations on the approach to Ceres.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] On the evening of Tuesday, January 18, 2022, a possible failure of one of the Swift Observatory's reaction wheels caused the mission control team to power off the suspected wheel, putting the observatory in safe mode as a precaution.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] This was the first time a reaction wheel failed on Swift in 17 years.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] Swift resumed science operations on February 17, 2022.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] A control moment gyroscope (CMG) is a related but different type of attitude actuator, generally consisting of a momentum wheel mounted in a one-axis or two-axis gimbal.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] When mounted to a rigid spacecraft, applying a constant torque to the wheel using one of the gimbal motors causes the spacecraft to develop a constant angular velocity about a perpendicular axis, thus allowing control of the spacecraft's pointing direction.
[src:satellite-systems/reaction-wheel] CMGs are generally able to produce larger sustained torques than RWs with less motor heating, and are preferentially used in larger or more-agile (or both) spacecraft, including Skylab, Mir, and the International Space Station.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite-bus] A **satellite bus** (or **spacecraft bus**) is the main body and structural component of a satellite or spacecraft, in which the payload and all scientific instruments are held.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite-bus] Bus-derived satellites are less customized than specially-produced satellites, but have specific equipment added to meet customer requirements, for example with specialized sensors or transponders, in order to achieve a specific mission.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite-bus] They are commonly used for geosynchronous satellites, particularly communications satellites, but are most commonly used in spacecraft which occupy low Earth orbit missions.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] A **satellite** or an **artificial satellite** is an object, typically a spacecraft, placed into orbit around a celestial body.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] They have a variety of uses, including communication relay, weather forecasting, navigation (GPS), broadcasting, scientific research, and Earth observation.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Additional military uses are reconnaissance, early warning, signals intelligence and, potentially, weapon delivery.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Other satellites include the final rocket stages that place satellites in orbit and formerly useful satellites that later become defunct.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Except for passive satellites, most satellites have an electricity generation system for equipment on board, such as solar panels or radioisotope thermoelectric generators (RTGs).
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Most satellites also have a method of communication to ground stations, called transponders.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Many satellites use a standardized bus to save cost and work, the most popular of which are small CubeSats.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Similar satellites can work together as groups, forming constellations.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Because of the high launch cost to space, most satellites are designed to be as lightweight and robust as possible.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Most communication satellites are radio relay stations in orbit and carry dozens of transponders, each with a bandwidth of tens of megahertz.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Spaceships become satellites by accelerating or decelerating to reach orbital velocities, occupying an orbit high enough to avoid orbital decay due to drag in the presence of an atmosphere and above their Roche limit.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Satellites are spacecraft launched from the surface into space by launch systems.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Satellites can then change or maintain their orbit by propulsion, usually by chemical or ion thrusters.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] As of 2018, about 90% of the satellites orbiting the Earth are in low Earth orbit or geostationary orbit; geostationary means the satellites stay still in the sky (relative to a fixed point on the ground).
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Some imaging satellites choose a Sun-synchronous orbit because they can scan the entire globe with similar lighting.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] As the number of satellites and amount of space debris around Earth increases, the threat of collision has become more severe.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] An **orbiter** is a spacecraft that is designed to perform an orbital insertion, entering orbit around an astronomical body from another, and as such becoming an artificial satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] A small number of satellites orbit other bodies (such as the Moon, Mars, and the Sun) or many bodies at once (two for a halo orbit, three for a Lissajous orbit).
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Earth observation satellites gather information for reconnaissance, mapping, monitoring the weather, ocean, forest, etc.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Space telescopes take advantage of outer space's near perfect vacuum to observe objects with the entire electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Because satellites can see a large portion of the Earth at once, communications satellites can relay information to remote places.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The signal delay from satellites and their orbit's predictability are used in satellite navigation systems, such as GPS.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Crewed spacecrafts which are in orbit or remain in orbit, like Space stations, are artificial satellites as well.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The first artificial satellite launched into the Earth's orbit was the Soviet Union's Sputnik 1, on October 4, 1957.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] As of June 28, 2025, there are 12,952 satellites in the Earth's orbit, of which 8,530 belong to the United States, 1,559 to Russia, and 908 to China.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The first published mathematical study of the possibility of an artificial satellite was Newton's cannonball, a thought experiment by Isaac Newton to explain the motion of natural satellites, in his *Philosophiæ Naturalis Principia Mathematica* (1687).
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The first fictional depiction of a satellite being launched into orbit was a short story by Edward Everett Hale, "The Brick Moon" (1869).
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The idea surfaced again in Jules Verne's *The Begum's Fortune* (1879).
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] In 1903, Konstantin Tsiolkovsky (1857–1935) published *Exploring Space Using Jet Propulsion Devices*, which was the first academic treatise on the use of rocketry to launch spacecraft.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] He calculated the orbital speed required for a minimal orbit, and inferred that a multi-stage rocket fueled by liquid propellants could achieve this.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Herman Potočnik explored the idea of using orbiting spacecraft for detailed peaceful and military observation of the ground in his 1928 book, *The Problem of Space Travel*.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] He described how the special conditions of space could be useful for scientific experiments.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The book described geostationary satellites (first put forward by Konstantin Tsiolkovsky) and discussed the communication between them and the ground using radio, but fell short with the idea of using satellites for mass broadcasting and as telecommunications relays.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] In a 1945 *Wireless World* article, English science fiction writer Arthur C.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Clarke described in detail the possible use of communications satellites for mass communications.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] He suggested that three geostationary satellites would provide coverage over the entire planet.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Project RAND eventually released the report, but considered the satellite to be a tool for science, politics, and propaganda, rather than a potential military weapon.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] In 1946, American theoretical astrophysicist Lyman Spitzer proposed an orbiting space telescope.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] In February 1954, Project RAND released "Scientific Uses for a Satellite Vehicle", by R.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] This expanded on potential scientific uses for satellite vehicles and was followed in June 1955 with "The Scientific Use of an Artificial Satellite", by H.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The first artificial satellite was Sputnik 1, launched by the Soviet Union on 4 October 1957 under the Sputnik program, with Sergei Korolev as chief designer.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Sputnik 1 helped to identify the density of high atmospheric layers through measurement of its orbital change and provided data on radio-signal distribution in the ionosphere.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The unanticipated announcement of Sputnik 1's success precipitated the Sputnik crisis in the United States and ignited the so-called Space Race within the Cold War.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] In the context of activities planned for the International Geophysical Year (1957–1958), the White House announced on 29 July 1955 that the U.S. intended to launch satellites by the spring of 1958.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] On 31 July, the Soviet Union announced its intention to launch a satellite by the fall of 1957.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Sputnik 2 was launched on 3 November 1957 and carried the first living passenger into orbit, a dog named Laika.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The dog was sent without possibility of return.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] In early 1955, after being pressured by the American Rocket Society, the National Science Foundation, and the International Geophysical Year, the Army and Navy worked on Project Orbiter with two competing programs.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The army used the Jupiter C rocket, while the civilian–Navy program used the Vanguard rocket to launch a satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Explorer 1 became the United States' first artificial satellite, on 31 January 1958.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The information sent back from its radiation detector led to the discovery of the Earth's Van Allen radiation belts.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The TIROS-1 spacecraft, launched on April 1, 1960, as part of NASA's Television Infrared Observation Satellite (TIROS) program, sent back the first television footage of weather patterns to be taken from space.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] In June 1961, three and a half years after the launch of Sputnik 1, the United States Space Surveillance Network cataloged 115 Earth-orbiting satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] While Canada was the third country to build a satellite which was launched into space, it was launched aboard an American rocket from an American spaceport.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The same goes for Australia, whose launch of the first satellite involved a donated U.S.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Redstone rocket and American support staff as well as a joint launch facility with the United Kingdom.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The first Italian satellite San Marco 1 was launched on 15 December 1964 on a U.S.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Scout rocket from Wallops Island (Virginia, United States) with an Italian launch team trained by NASA.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] In similar occasions, almost all further first national satellites were launched by foreign rockets.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] France was the third country to launch a satellite on its own rocket.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] On 26 November 1965, the Astérix or A-1 (initially conceptualized as FR.2 or FR-2), was put into orbit by a Diamant A rocket launched from the CIEES site at Hammaguir, Algeria.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] With Astérix, France became the sixth country to have an artificial satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Early satellites were built to unique designs.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] With advancements in technology, multiple satellites began to be built on single model platforms called satellite buses.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The first standardized satellite bus design was the HS-333 geosynchronous (GEO) communication satellite launched in 1972.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Beginning in 1997, FreeFlyer is a commercial off-the-shelf software application for satellite mission analysis, design, and operations.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The largest artificial satellite ever is the International Space Station.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] By the early 2000s, and particularly after the advent of CubeSats and increased launches of microsats—frequently launched to the lower altitudes of low Earth orbit (LEO)—satellites began to more frequently be designed to get destroyed, or breakup and burnup entirely in the atmosphere.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] For example, SpaceX Starlink satellites, the first large satellite internet constellation to exceed 1000 active satellites on orbit in 2020, are designed to be 100% demisable and burn up completely on their atmospheric reentry at the end of their life, or in the event of an early satellite failure.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Japan's space agency (JAXA) and NASA plan to send a wooden satellite prototype called LingoSat into orbit in the summer of 2024.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] They have been working on this project for few years and sent first wood samples to the space in 2021 to test the material's resilience to space conditions.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Most satellites use chemical or ion propulsion to adjust or maintain their orbit, coupled with reaction wheels to control their three axis of rotation or attitude.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Satellites close to Earth are affected the most by variations in the Earth's magnetic, gravitational field and the Sun's radiation pressure; satellites that are further away are affected more by other bodies' gravitational field by the Moon and the Sun.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Satellites utilize ultra-white reflective coatings to prevent damage from UV radiation.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Without orbit and orientation control, satellites in orbit will not be able to communicate with ground stations on the Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Chemical thrusters on satellites usually use monopropellant (one-part) or bipropellant (two-parts) that are hypergolic.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Hypergolic means able to combust spontaneously when in contact with each other or to a catalyst.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The most commonly used propellant mixtures on satellites are hydrazine-based monopropellants or monomethylhydrazine–dinitrogen tetroxide bipropellants.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Ion thrusters on satellites usually are Hall-effect thrusters, which generate thrust by accelerating positive ions through a negatively-charged grid.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Ion propulsion is more efficient propellant-wise than chemical propulsion but its thrust is very small (around 0.5 N or 0.1 lbf), and thus requires a longer burn time.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The thrusters usually use xenon because it is inert, can be easily ionized, has a high atomic mass and storable as a high-pressure liquid.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Most satellites use solar panels to generate power, and a few in deep space with limited sunlight use radioisotope thermoelectric generators.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Slip rings attach solar panels to the satellite; the slip rings can rotate to be perpendicular with the sunlight and generate the most power.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] All satellites with a solar panel must also have batteries, because sunlight is blocked inside the launch vehicle and at night.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The most common types of batteries for satellites are lithium-ion, and in the past nickel–hydrogen.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Earth observation satellites are designed to monitor and survey the Earth, called remote sensing.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Most Earth observation satellites are placed in low Earth orbit for a high data resolution, though some are placed in a geostationary orbit for an uninterrupted coverage.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Some satellites are placed in a Sun-synchronous orbit to have consistent lighting and obtain a total view of the Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Depending on the satellites' functions, they might have a normal camera, radar, lidar, photometer, or atmospheric instruments.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Earth observation satellite's data is most used in archaeology, cartography, environmental monitoring, meteorology, and reconnaissance applications.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] As of 2021, there are over 950 Earth observation satellites, with the largest number of satellites operated with Planet Labs.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Weather satellites monitor clouds, city lights, fires, effects of pollution, auroras, sand and dust storms, snow cover, ice mapping, boundaries of ocean currents, energy flows, etc.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Environmental monitoring satellites can detect changes in the Earth's vegetation, atmospheric trace gas content, sea state, ocean color, and ice fields.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] By monitoring vegetation changes over time, droughts can be monitored by comparing the current vegetation state to its long term average.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Anthropogenic emissions can be monitored by evaluating data of tropospheric NO2 and SO2.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] A communications satellite is an artificial satellite that relays and amplifies radio telecommunication signals via a transponder; it creates a communication channel between a source transmitter and a receiver at different locations on Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] When an Earth observation satellite or a communications satellite is deployed for military or intelligence purposes, it is known as a spy satellite or reconnaissance satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Their uses include early missile warning, nuclear explosion detection, electronic reconnaissance, and optical or radar imaging surveillance.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Navigational satellites are satellites that use radio time signals transmitted to enable mobile receivers on the ground to determine their exact location.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The relatively clear line of sight between the satellites and receivers on the ground, combined with ever-improving electronics, allows satellite navigation systems to measure location to accuracies on the order of a few meters in real time.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Astronomical satellites are satellites used for observation of distant planets, galaxies, and other outer space objects.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Tether satellites are satellites that are connected to another satellite by a thin cable called a tether.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Recovery satellites are satellites that provide a recovery of reconnaissance, biological, space-production and other payloads from orbit to Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Biosatellites are satellites designed to carry living organisms, generally for scientific experimentation.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Space-based solar power satellites are proposed satellites that would collect energy from sunlight and transmit it for use on Earth or other places.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Since the mid-2000s, satellites have been hacked by militant organizations to broadcast propaganda and to pilfer classified information from military communication networks.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] For testing purposes, satellites in low earth orbit have been destroyed by ballistic missiles launched from the Earth.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Russia, United States, China and India have demonstrated the ability to eliminate satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] In 2007, the Chinese military shot down an aging weather satellite, followed by the US Navy shooting down a defunct spy satellite in February 2008.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] On 18 November 2015, after two failed attempts, Russia successfully carried out a flight test of an anti-satellite missile known as *Nudol*.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] On 27 March 2019, India shot down a live test satellite at 300 km altitude in 3 minutes, becoming the fourth country to have the capability to destroy live satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The environmental impact of satellites is not currently well understood as they were previously assumed to be benign due to the rarity of satellite launches.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] However, the exponential increase and projected growth of satellite launches are bringing the issue into consideration.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The main issues are resource use and the release of pollutants into the atmosphere which can happen at different stages of a satellite's lifetime.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Resource use is difficult to monitor and quantify for satellites and launch vehicles due to their commercially sensitive nature.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] However, aluminium is a preferred metal in satellite construction due to its lightweight and relative cheapness and typically constitutes around 40% of a satellite's mass.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Through mining and refining, aluminium has numerous negative environmental impacts and is one of the most carbon-intensive metals.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Satellite manufacturing also requires rare elements such as lithium, gold, and gallium, some of which have significant environmental consequences linked to their mining and processing and/or are in limited supply.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Launch vehicles require larger amounts of raw materials to manufacture and the booster stages are usually dropped into the ocean after fuel exhaustion.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Two empty boosters used for Ariane 5, which were composed mainly of steel, weighed around 38 tons each, to give an idea of the quantity of materials that are often left in the ocean.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Rocket launches release numerous pollutants into every layer of the atmosphere, especially affecting the atmosphere above the tropopause where the byproducts of combustion can reside for extended periods.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] These pollutants can include black carbon, CO2, nitrogen oxides (NOx), aluminium and water vapour, but the mix of pollutants is dependent on rocket design and fuel type.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The amount of green house gases emitted by rockets is considered trivial as it contributes significantly less, around 0.01%, than the aviation industry yearly which itself accounts for 2-3% of the total global greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Rocket emissions in the stratosphere and their effects are only beginning to be studied and it is likely that the impacts will be more critical than emissions in the troposphere.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The stratosphere includes the ozone layer and pollutants emitted from rockets can contribute to ozone depletion in a number of ways.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Radicals such as NOx, HOx, and ClOx deplete stratospheric O3 through intermolecular reactions and can have huge impacts in trace amounts.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] However, it is currently understood that launch rates would need to increase by ten times to match the impact of regulated ozone-depleting substances.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Whilst emissions of water vapour are largely deemed as inert, H2O is the source gas for HOx and can also contribute to ozone loss through the formation of ice particles.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Black carbon particles emitted by rockets can absorb solar radiation in the stratosphere and cause warming in the surrounding air which can then impact the circulatory dynamics of the stratosphere.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Both warming and changes in circulation can then cause depletion of the ozone layer.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Several pollutants are released in the upper atmospheric layers during the orbital lifetime of LEO satellites.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Orbital decay is caused by atmospheric drag and to keep the satellite in the correct orbit the platform occasionally needs repositioning.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] To do this nozzle-based systems use a chemical propellant to create thrust.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] In most cases hydrazine is the chemical propellant used which then releases ammonia, hydrogen and nitrogen as gas into the upper atmosphere.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Also, the environment of the outer atmosphere causes the degradation of exterior materials.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The atomic oxygen in the upper atmosphere oxidises hydrocarbon-based polymers like Kapton, Teflon and Mylar that are used to insulate and protect the satellite which then emits gasses like CO2 and CO into the atmosphere.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Given the current surge in satellites in the sky, soon hundreds of satellites may be clearly visible to the human eye at dark sites.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] It is estimated that the overall levels of diffuse brightness of the night skies has increased by up to 10% above natural levels.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] This has the potential to confuse organisms, like insects and night-migrating birds, that use celestial patterns for migration and orientation.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The impact this might have is currently unclear.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The visibility of human-made objects in the night sky may also impact people's linkages with the world, nature, and culture.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] At all points of a satellite's lifetime, its movement and processes are monitored on the ground through a network of facilities.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The environmental cost of the infrastructure as well as day-to-day operations is likely to be quite high, but quantification requires further investigation.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Particular threats arise from uncontrolled de-orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Some notable satellite failures that polluted and dispersed radioactive materials are Kosmos 954, Kosmos 1402 and the Transit 5-BN-3.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] When in a controlled manner satellites reach the end of life they are intentionally deorbited or moved to a graveyard orbit further away from Earth in order to reduce space debris.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Physical collection or removal is not economical or even currently possible.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Moving satellites out to a graveyard orbit is also unsustainable because they remain there for hundreds of years.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] It will lead to the further pollution of space and future issues with space debris.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] When satellites deorbit much of it is destroyed during re-entry into the atmosphere due to the heat.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] This introduces more material and pollutants into the atmosphere.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] There have been concerns expressed about the potential damage to the ozone layer and the possibility of increasing the earth's albedo, reducing warming but also resulting in accidental geoengineering of the earth's climate.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] After deorbiting 70% of satellites end up in the ocean and are rarely recovered.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Using wood as an alternative material has been posited in order to reduce pollution and debris from satellites that reenter the atmosphere.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Space debris pose dangers to the spacecraft (including satellites) in or crossing geocentric orbits and have the potential to drive a Kessler syndrome which could potentially curtail humanity from conducting space endeavors in the future.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] With increase in the number of satellite constellations, like SpaceX Starlink, the astronomical community, such as the IAU, report that orbital pollution is increasing significantly.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] A report from the SATCON1 workshop in 2020 concluded that the effects of large satellite constellations can severely affect some astronomical research efforts and lists six ways to mitigate harm to astronomy.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The IAU is establishing a center (CPS) to coordinate or aggregate measures to mitigate such detrimental effects.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Due to the low received signal strength of satellite transmissions, they are prone to jamming by land-based transmitters.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Such jamming is limited to the geographical area within the transmitter's range.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] GPS satellites are potential targets for jamming, but satellite phone and television signals have also been subjected to jamming.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Also, it is very easy to transmit a carrier radio signal to a geostationary satellite and thus interfere with the legitimate uses of the satellite's transponder.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] It is common for Earth stations to transmit at the wrong time or on the wrong frequency in commercial satellite space, and dual-illuminate the transponder, rendering the frequency unusable.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Satellite operators now have sophisticated monitoring tools and methods that enable them to pinpoint the source of any carrier and manage the transponder space effectively.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Issues like space debris, radio and light pollution are increasing in magnitude and at the same time lack progress in national or international regulation.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Generally liability has been covered by the Liability Convention.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] The operation capabilities and use have very much diversified and is broadening increasingly.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Satellite operation needs not only access to financial, manufacturing and launch capabilities, but also a ground segment infrastructure.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] A list of selected Earth satellites with a high mass is given.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Excluded are crewed satellites i.e. space stations and launch vehicles, and satellites not intended for long-term Earth orbit, such as missions to beyond Earth orbit.
[src:satellite-systems/satellite] Included are satellites at Sun-Earth Lagrange point 2.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] A communications satellite's transponder is the series of interconnected units that form a communications channel between the receiving and the transmitting antennas.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] It is mainly used in satellite communication to transfer the received signals.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] Most transponders operate on a **bent pipe** (i.e., u-bend) principle, sending back to Earth what goes into the conduit with only amplification and a shift from uplink to downlink frequency.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] However, some modern satellites use on-board processing, where the signal is demodulated, decoded, re-encoded and modulated aboard the satellite.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] This type, called a "regenerative" transponder, is more complex, but has many advantages, such as improving the signal to noise ratio as the signal is regenerated from the digital domain, and also permits selective processing of the data in the digital domain.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] With data compression and multiplexing, several video (including digital video) and audio channels may travel through a single transponder on a single wideband carrier.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] Original analog video only had one channel per transponder, with subcarriers for audio and automatic transmission-identification service ATIS.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] Non-multiplexed radio stations can also travel in single channel per carrier (SCPC) mode, with multiple carriers (analog or digital) per transponder.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] This allows each station to transmit directly to the satellite, rather than paying for a whole transponder or using landlines to send it to an Earth station for multiplexing with other stations.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] NASA distinguishes between a "transceiver" and "transponder".
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] A transceiver has an independent transmitter and receiver packaged in the same unit.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] In a transponder the transmit carrier frequency is derived from the received signal.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] The frequency linkage allows an interrogating ground station to recover the Doppler shift and thus infer range and speed from a communication signal without allocating power to a separate ranging signal.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] A **transponder equivalent** (**TPE**) is a normalized way to refer to transponder bandwidth.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] It simply means how many transponders would be used if the same total bandwidths used only 36 MHz transponders.
[src:satellite-systems/transponder-satellite-communications] So, for example, the ARSAT-1 has 24 IEEE Ku band transponders: 12 with a bandwidth of 36 MHz, 8 with 54 MHz, and 4 with 72 MHz, which totals to 1152 MHz, or 32 TPE (i.e., 1152 MHz divided by 36 MHz).
